const e=[{id:"dev",name:"Developer",icon:"💻",color:"var(--sky)",blurb:"Logic, edge cases, complexity and debugging.",questions:[{t:"Logic",q:"A function works for every input except 0, where it crashes. The most likely cause is…",o:["a slow algorithm","an unhandled edge case","a typo in a comment","too much memory"],a:1,e:"A failure isolated to one special value is the signature of a missing edge-case check."},{t:"Pattern",q:"What number continues the sequence?",v:"1  1  2  3  5  8  ?",o:["11","12","13","15"],a:2,e:"Each term is the sum of the previous two (Fibonacci): 5 + 8 = 13."},{t:"Logic",q:'Rule: "Every valid user has a token." A request has no token. What follows?',o:["the user is valid","the user is not valid","the token expired","nothing"],a:1,e:"Contrapositive: no token means not a valid user."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Doubling the input size roughly doubles the running time. The complexity is about…",o:["O(1)","O(n)","O(n²)","O(log n)"],a:1,e:"Time scaling in direct proportion is linear, O(n)."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Two functions return identical output, but one is 100× slower. Inspect first…",o:["variable names","code comments","loops & data structures","file size"],a:2,e:"Large speed gaps come from algorithmic work, not cosmetics."},{t:"Logic",q:"Code works on your machine but crashes on the server. The likely culprit is…",o:["the keyboard","an environment/config difference","bad luck","the monitor"],a:1,e:'"Works on my machine" almost always means the environments differ — versions, config or data.'},{t:"Numbers",q:"A list has 1,000,000 items. A linear search may check up to about…",o:["10","1,000","1,000,000","10"],a:2,e:"Linear search can scan every item — up to a million checks."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A bug appears once a week at random. Best first step?",o:["rewrite everything","add logging to capture it","ignore it","blame the user"],a:1,e:"Rare, intermittent bugs need data — logging captures the conditions when it strikes."},{t:"Logic",q:"A test passes locally but fails in the CI pipeline. The most likely difference is…",o:["the language changed","the environment or config differs","the test failed by luck","nothing at all"],a:1,e:"CI runs elsewhere — versions, env vars or config usually differ."},{t:"Numbers",q:"An array has 8 sorted items. A binary search checks at most about…",o:["8","4","3","1"],a:2,e:"About log2(8) = 3 checks."},{t:"Logic",q:"A variable still holds yesterday's value. The most likely cause is…",o:["the screen","a stale cache or value never refreshed","the keyboard","the font"],a:1,e:"Old data usually means a cache or a value that was never re-read."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A page is slow only for some users. First compare their…",o:["names","device, network or data size","star sign","keyboard colour"],a:1,e:"Selective slowness tracks differences in device, connection or data volume."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A loop nested inside another loop over n items does about…",o:["n steps","2n steps","n² steps","log n steps"],a:2,e:"Nested loops over n give roughly n × n = n² work."},{t:"Logic",q:"Two services must agree on a value but sometimes disagree. The usual root cause is…",o:["colour","a race condition — timing","the keyboard","the font"],a:1,e:"Concurrent updates without coordination cause races."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Adding a database index made writes slower. Why?",o:["indexes are free","each write must also update the index","writes never change data","no reason"],a:1,e:"Indexes speed reads but add work to every write."},{t:"Logic",q:"A feature works for 1 user but breaks for 1,000 at once. You likely hit a…",o:["typo","scaling or concurrency limit","colour bug","font issue"],a:1,e:"Load exposes limits a single user never triggers."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Caching turns a 200 ms call into a 2 ms call — about…",o:["10× faster","2× faster","100× faster","no change"],a:2,e:"200 ÷ 2 = 100, so roughly 100× faster."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A test passes 9 times then fails once. The usual cause is…",o:["pure luck","hidden timing or shared state","the test name","too few tests"],a:1,e:"Flakiness usually comes from timing or shared, mutable state."},{t:"Logic",q:"By the CAP theorem, a system must stay available during a network split by giving up…",o:["availability","strong consistency","partition tolerance","all three"],a:1,e:"During a partition you trade consistency to keep availability."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Sorting n items with a good comparison sort takes about…",o:["n","n log n","n²","log n"],a:1,e:"Efficient comparison sorts are O(n log n)."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Latency is fine but throughput stalls under load. The bottleneck is most likely…",o:["a single shared resource or lock","the icon","the colour scheme","the font"],a:0,e:"A contended shared resource caps how much work flows through."},{t:"Logic",q:"An idempotent API call can safely be…",o:["called only once","retried with the same effect","never retried","deleted"],a:1,e:"Idempotency means repeating the call has the same result — safe to retry."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A query is fast on 1k rows but crawls on 10M. The fix is usually…",o:["a faster mouse","an index or better query plan","a bigger monitor","more browser tabs"],a:1,e:"At scale, indexing and the query plan dominate."},{t:"Logic",q:"Events arrive out of order across machines. To order them reliably you use…",o:["wall clocks only","logical timestamps or version vectors","colour codes","the alphabet"],a:1,e:"Clocks drift; logical timestamps order events safely."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Doubling servers cuts response time far less than half. This points to…",o:["perfect scaling","a serial, non-parallel part","a typo","more RAM needed"],a:1,e:"A non-parallel portion limits speedup — Amdahl's law."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A retry storm makes an outage worse. A good safeguard is…",o:["retry faster","backoff with jitter","infinite retries","no logging"],a:1,e:"Exponential backoff with jitter stops synchronized retry floods."},{t:"Logic",q:"Caching can serve stale data after an update. The core tension is between…",o:["speed and freshness","red and blue","up and down","big and small"],a:0,e:"Caching trades freshness for speed; invalidation manages the gap."},{t:"Lateral",q:"One slow downstream service drags your whole API down. A resilient fix is…",o:["ignore it","a timeout plus circuit breaker","retry forever","remove logging"],a:1,e:"Timeouts and circuit breakers isolate a failing dependency."},{t:"Lateral",q:"An app uses more and more memory until it crashes. This pattern is a…",o:["feature","memory leak","fast app","cache hit"],a:1,e:"Memory that grows and is never freed is a leak."},{t:"Logic",q:"Removing duplicated logic into one place means a future fix needs…",o:["two edits","one edit","no edits","three edits"],a:1,e:"One shared place means one change fixes everything — the point of DRY."}]},{id:"doctor",name:"Doctor",icon:"🩺",color:"var(--berry)",blurb:"Diagnostic reasoning, probability and risk.",questions:[{t:"Logic",q:"A disease affects 1 in 10,000. A test is 99% accurate. A patient tests positive. Most likely they…",o:["definitely have it","probably do NOT have it","have a mild case","need no follow-up"],a:1,e:"With a very rare disease, false positives outnumber true ones — base rates dominate."},{t:"Logic",q:"Symptom X occurs in diseases A and B. Symptom Y only in A. A patient shows both. Likely diagnosis?",o:["A","B","neither","cannot tell"],a:0,e:"Y points only to A, and the patient has Y."},{t:"Logic",q:'Rule: "If infection, then fever." This patient has no fever. So they…',o:["have an infection","do not have an infection","have a virus","need antibiotics"],a:1,e:"Contrapositive: no fever means no infection under this rule."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Treatment A helps 80% with mild side effects. B helps 82% with severe ones. Reasonable first choice?",o:["B, it is higher","A, better risk/benefit","neither","flip a coin"],a:1,e:"A 2% gain rarely justifies severe harm."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A heart beats ~70 times a minute. Roughly how many beats in an hour?",o:["700","1,400","4,200","42,000"],a:2,e:"70 × 60 ≈ 4,200."},{t:"Logic",q:"A patient improves after a treatment with no proven effect. Most likely…",o:["a miracle","placebo or natural recovery","proof it works","impossible"],a:1,e:"Improvement alone does not prove cause — placebo and natural healing confound it."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A drip gives 20 drops per minute. Roughly how many in 5 minutes?",o:["25","60","100","200"],a:2,e:"20 × 5 = 100 drops."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Two patients share every symptom but one is far sicker. Most worth checking is…",o:["their names","vital signs and history","the room number","the time"],a:1,e:"Objective vitals and history reveal severity beyond matching symptoms."},{t:"Logic",q:"A patient improves only on days they take the medicine. This suggests it is…",o:["useless","likely helping","harmful","random"],a:1,e:"Improvement tracking the dose suggests a real effect."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Two illnesses share one symptom. To tell them apart you look for…",o:["the shared symptom","a symptom only one has","the patient name","the room number"],a:1,e:"A distinguishing symptom separates similar conditions."},{t:"Logic",q:"A test that catches 95 out of every 100 people who truly have the disease has high…",o:["specificity","sensitivity","positive predictive value","accuracy"],a:1,e:"Sensitivity is the true-positive rate — the higher it is, the fewer sick people the test misses."},{t:"Logic",q:"A test that correctly clears 98 out of 100 healthy people has high…",o:["sensitivity","recall","specificity","incidence"],a:2,e:"Specificity is the true-negative rate — minimising false alarms in people who are well."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A treatment prevents a complication in 4 out of 200 patients. The Number Needed to Treat is…",o:["4","50","200","40"],a:1,e:"NNT = 1 ÷ absolute risk reduction = 1 ÷ (4/200) = 50 patients treated per event prevented."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Coffee drinkers are less likely to get disease X — but they also smoke far less. Before concluding coffee protects, you must rule out…",o:["the coffee brand","smoking as a confounding variable","the study country","the time of day"],a:1,e:"A confounder correlates with both the exposure and the outcome, creating a spurious apparent association."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A drug halves relative risk — from 4% down to 2%. The absolute risk reduction is…",o:["50%","2%","25%","4%"],a:1,e:"The relative halving sounds dramatic; the absolute gain is just 2 percentage points — context is everything."},{t:"Logic",q:"Participants in a drug trial are randomly allocated to groups mainly so that…",o:["costs are cut","known and unknown confounders are spread evenly across arms","placebo patients recover faster","doctors choose who gets treatment"],a:1,e:"Randomisation distributes all variables — measured or not — letting the treatment effect emerge without bias."},{t:"Logic",q:"Neither the patients nor the clinicians assessing outcomes know who received the real drug. The trial design is called…",o:["open-label","single-blind","double-blind","uncontrolled"],a:2,e:"Double-blinding prevents expectation from distorting both the patient's experience and the assessor's judgement."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A screening programme reports doubled 5-year survival compared with historical cases. Before crediting better treatment, consider that earlier detection alone could inflate survival time even if…",o:["the test is inexpensive","the cancer's natural course is completely unchanged","the patients are younger","the study is government-funded"],a:1,e:"Lead-time bias: shifting the clock start to earlier detection inflates apparent survival without extending actual life."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Pooling data from 20 similar studies gives a more reliable effect estimate than any single study because it…",o:["trusts the largest study only","reduces random error across a much larger combined sample","averages p-values arithmetically","automatically excludes null results"],a:1,e:"Meta-analysis narrows confidence intervals and smooths out chance findings that inflate single-study results."},{t:"Logic",q:"Positive Predictive Value answers: given a positive test result, what is the probability that…",o:["the test equipment is calibrated","the patient genuinely has the disease","the disease is prevalent","sensitivity exceeds 90%"],a:1,e:"PPV depends heavily on disease prevalence — in rare conditions even an accurate test produces many false positives."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Slow-growing tumours spend more time in the detectable-but-asymptomatic window, so screening catches them disproportionately — making screened cancers appear less deadly than average. This is…",o:["lead-time bias","length-time bias","ascertainment bias","recall bias"],a:1,e:"Length-time bias: screening preferentially harvests indolent disease, artificially flattering survival statistics."},{t:"Logic",q:"Journals publish far more trials showing drug benefits than trials showing no effect. The literature therefore…",o:["perfectly represents all conducted research","overstates treatment efficacy because null results stay in file drawers","underestimates side-effect rates only","is unaffected by what remains unpublished"],a:1,e:"Publication bias inflates the apparent record of treatments — a systematic distortion, not random noise."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A very high blood pressure reading returns to normal at the next visit without any treatment. This most commonly reflects…",o:["a spontaneous cure","regression to the mean — extreme measurements drift back toward the average on re-test","equipment failure","an unusual nocebo response"],a:1,e:"Regression to the mean: measurements far from average at first visit tend toward average values at second."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Disease prevalence is 10%. A test has 90% sensitivity and 90% specificity. After a positive result, the probability of truly having the disease is roughly…",o:["90%","50%","10%","99%"],a:1,e:"Bayes' theorem with 10% prior and a 90/90 test yields approximately 50% posterior — base rate shapes everything."},{t:"Logic",q:"Patients who dropped out of a trial were mostly experiencing side effects. Analysing only completers would make the drug appear…",o:["less effective","more effective and safer than it truly is","equally effective","too expensive"],a:1,e:"Intention-to-treat keeps all randomised participants in their original group, preventing selective survivor bias."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Hospital A treats mostly frail elderly patients; Hospital B treats fit younger adults. Comparing raw mortality rates directly unfairly penalises…",o:["Hospital B","Hospital A — its sicker patient mix raises expected mortality regardless of care quality","both hospitals equally","neither hospital"],a:1,e:"Case-mix adjustment accounts for patient severity — without it, harder cases punish the hospitals that take them."},{t:"Logic",q:"A patient told that a drug commonly causes nausea then reports nausea — yet pharmacologically the drug cannot cause it. This is…",o:["the placebo effect","the nocebo effect","observer bias","regression to the mean"],a:1,e:"Nocebo: negative expectation generates real negative outcomes — the dark counterpart of the placebo effect."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A drug causes a serious adverse event in 1 in 25 patients treated. The Number Needed to Harm is…",o:["1","5","25","100"],a:2,e:"NNH = 1 ÷ absolute risk of harm = 1 ÷ 0.04 = 25."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A case-control study recruits its control group from the same hospital as the cases. Hospital controls are already sicker than the general public, shrinking the apparent risk difference. This flaw is…",o:["lead-time bias","length-time bias","Berkson's bias","detection bias"],a:2,e:"Berkson's bias: hospital-based controls over-represent illness, distorting odds ratios away from the true population effect."},{t:"Logic",q:"Detecting an effect that does not exist — falsely rejecting a true null hypothesis — is called a…",o:["Type II error","Type I error (false positive)","power failure","replication error"],a:1,e:"Type I error rate equals the alpha threshold. Setting alpha at 0.05 means accepting a 5% chance of a false alarm."}]},{id:"lawyer",name:"Lawyer",icon:"⚖️",color:"var(--lantern)",blurb:"Conditional logic, evidence and argument.",questions:[{t:"Logic",q:'Rule: "If signed, the contract is binding." This one is NOT binding. Therefore it was…',o:["signed","not signed","witnessed","verbal"],a:1,e:"Contrapositive: not binding means not signed."},{t:"Verbal",q:"Which is the strongest form of evidence?",o:["a rumour","an eyewitness guess","a signed dated document","a hunch"],a:2,e:"A signed, dated document is concrete and verifiable."},{t:"Logic",q:"Every valid contract here needs two signatures. This one has only one. It is…",o:["valid","invalid","pending","renewed"],a:1,e:"A required condition is unmet, so it is invalid."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A clause can honestly be read two ways. Best first move is to…",o:["pick the one you prefer","define terms / seek clarification","ignore the clause","sign quickly"],a:1,e:"Resolve ambiguity by clarifying definitions and intent."},{t:"Logic",q:'Rule: "No one under 18 may sign." A 17-year-old signed. The signature is…',o:["valid","invalid","optional","binding"],a:1,e:"They fall in the prohibited category, so it does not count."},{t:"Logic",q:'"If A then B." You know B is true. Can you conclude A?',o:["yes","no","always","guaranteed"],a:1,e:"Affirming the consequent is a fallacy — B can be true for other reasons."},{t:"Verbal",q:"Which is a fact, not an opinion?",o:['"The film was boring"','"Signed on May 3"','"He seems guilty"','"It feels unfair"'],a:1,e:"A dated signing is verifiable; the rest are judgements."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A witness is confident but was 100m away at night. Their account is…",o:["fully reliable","weighed against the conditions","irrelevant","proof"],a:1,e:"Confidence is not accuracy; conditions affecting perception must be weighed."},{t:"Logic",q:"A contract says either party may cancel with 30 days notice. Cancelling today takes effect in…",o:["immediately","about 30 days","one year","never"],a:1,e:"The notice period delays the effect by 30 days."},{t:"Verbal",q:"A clause can be read two ways. The safest drafting fix is to…",o:["leave it vague","define the term clearly","delete the contract","add more vague words"],a:1,e:"Precise definitions remove ambiguity."},{t:"Logic",q:"Evidence gathered via an unlawful search is excluded under the doctrine of…",o:["hearsay","the fruit of the poisonous tree","double jeopardy","stare decisis"],a:1,e:"Evidence tainted by a constitutional violation cannot be admitted — the unlawful act poisons what flows from it."},{t:"Verbal",q:"Hearsay is an out-of-court statement offered to prove…",o:["the speaker's credibility","the truth of what it asserts","a legal procedure was followed","the witness was present"],a:1,e:"Hearsay risks are about unreliable second-hand proof — courts prefer direct, cross-examinable testimony."},{t:"Logic",q:"In a civil dispute the standard of proof is…",o:["beyond reasonable doubt","on the balance of probabilities","absolute certainty","any evidence whatsoever"],a:1,e:"Civil courts ask: is it more likely than not? Criminal courts demand the higher standard of beyond reasonable doubt."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A defendant was acquitted at trial. The prosecutor wants to try them again on the same charge. This is barred by…",o:["hearsay rules","double jeopardy","the statute of limitations","stare decisis"],a:1,e:"Double jeopardy prevents the state from repeatedly trying a person for the same offence — a fundamental protection."},{t:"Logic",q:"Stare decisis requires courts to…",o:["ignore older rulings","follow relevant prior decisions when the facts are materially similar","retry all past cases","create new rules each sitting"],a:1,e:'Stare decisis — "let the decision stand" — gives the law consistency and predictability through binding precedent.'},{t:"Verbal",q:"A statute of limitations sets the…",o:["minimum sentence","maximum time window in which a legal claim must be brought","filing fee","length of a trial"],a:1,e:"Miss the limitation period and the right to sue is lost permanently — the law promotes timely resolution of disputes."},{t:"Logic",q:"A defendant's unrelated prior criminal record is generally withheld from the jury because it…",o:["is always irrelevant","risks unfair prejudice — jurors may convict for character rather than the act charged","is sealed by default","proves innocence"],a:1,e:"Prior convictions speak to character, not to whether the defendant committed this specific act."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A documented chain of custody for physical evidence exists to show that the item…",o:["was expensive to collect","was not tampered with or substituted between collection and court","was found by a senior officer","matches the crime scene photo"],a:1,e:"Any break in the chain raises doubt about whether the exhibit in court is genuinely the same item from the scene."},{t:"Logic",q:"Proximate cause in tort requires that the defendant's act was the…",o:["most distant cause imaginable","legally recognised, direct cause of the claimant's harm","least foreseeable factor","purely moral cause"],a:1,e:"Proximate cause is the close, foreseeable link between act and injury — remote or unforeseeable harm is outside liability."},{t:"Verbal",q:"An expert witness, unlike a lay witness, is permitted to give…",o:["only what they personally observed","opinions and conclusions within their specialist field","hearsay evidence freely","evidence without cross-examination"],a:1,e:"Experts are invited precisely because they can draw inferences beyond raw facts — within their verified expertise."},{t:"Logic",q:"Mens rea in criminal law refers to…",o:["the physical act itself","the guilty mind or criminal intent behind the act","the victim's conduct","the sentence imposed"],a:1,e:"Most serious crimes require both actus reus (the act) and mens rea (the mental element). Without intent, no crime."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A contract signed under serious duress is…",o:["automatically criminal","voidable at the option of the coerced party","forever binding on both sides","valid if witnessed"],a:1,e:"Duress negates free consent — the law allows the wronged party to set the contract aside."},{t:"Verbal",q:"A fiduciary duty legally obligates one party to act in…",o:["their own commercial interest","the best interests of the person who relies on and trusts them","the public interest","the government's interest"],a:1,e:"Fiduciaries — trustees, solicitors, company directors — owe undivided loyalty to those who depend on them."},{t:"Logic",q:'Res ipsa loquitur ("the thing speaks for itself") assists a claimant by…',o:["proving intent automatically","raising an inference of negligence, shifting the burden to the defendant to explain","awarding damages immediately","replacing all other evidence"],a:1,e:"Where an accident could not occur without negligence, the defendant must account for it — the event speaks for itself."},{t:"Logic",q:"A claimant who was partly at fault for their own injury typically receives…",o:["full damages","reduced damages proportional to their share of fault","no damages at all","punitive damages"],a:1,e:"Contributory negligence apportions responsibility — the claimant's own fault reduces what they can recover."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A contract becomes impossible to perform because of a supervening, unforeseeable event beyond both parties' control. The contract is said to be…",o:["void from the start","frustrated — both parties are discharged from future obligations","in breach","criminal"],a:1,e:"Frustration discharges obligations when circumstances make performance radically different from what was agreed."},{t:"Logic",q:"Judicial review of a public authority examines whether it acted within its legal powers. Acting outside those powers is called…",o:["in limine","ultra vires","sub judice","nisi prius"],a:1,e:'Ultra vires — "beyond the powers" — is the foundational ground for reviewing decisions of public bodies.'},{t:"Verbal",q:'Negotiations conducted "without prejudice" protect the parties because those communications…',o:["are automatically binding","cannot generally be used as admissions in later litigation","are disclosed to the judge","require court approval"],a:1,e:'"Without prejudice" lets parties negotiate freely — admissions in settlement talks stay out of the courtroom.'},{t:"Logic",q:"An employer is vicariously liable for an employee's wrongful act only when it was committed…",o:["anywhere at any time","in the course of employment — sufficiently connected to the job","outside working hours","in writing"],a:1,e:"Purely personal acts done on a frolic of the employee's own do not bind the employer."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A consumer contract clause that excludes all liability for personal injury caused by the business's negligence is…",o:["enforceable if signed clearly","void and unenforceable under consumer protection statute","valid if printed in bold","good commercial practice"],a:1,e:"Statute prohibits excluding liability for death or personal injury caused by negligence — signature does not save it."}]},{id:"designer",name:"Designer",icon:"🎨",color:"var(--clay)",blurb:"Spatial reasoning, hierarchy, framing.",questions:[{t:"Spatial",q:"A busy layout feels stressful. The simplest fix is usually to…",o:["add more colours","add whitespace","make text bigger","add more icons"],a:1,e:"Breathing room reduces visual noise."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Every element on a screen is equally bold and large. The fix is to…",o:["shrink everything","establish a clear hierarchy","remove all colour","add animation"],a:1,e:"When everything shouts, nothing is heard."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Many users miss an important button. The most likely cause is…",o:["users are careless","low contrast or placement","the wrong font","too few users"],a:1,e:"Blame the design first: visibility and placement guide attention."},{t:"Spatial",q:"Reflecting a shape across a vertical line creates…",o:["a rotation","symmetry","a gradient","a shadow"],a:1,e:"Mirroring across an axis produces symmetry."},{t:"Pattern",q:'Two buttons are green, one is red. Which most likely means "stop"?',o:["a green one","the red one","none","all"],a:1,e:"Red is the shared signal for stop or danger."},{t:"Spatial",q:"To draw the eye to one button, make it…",o:["same as the rest","clearly contrast in colour/size","smaller","hidden"],a:1,e:"Contrast creates focus — the standout element gets noticed."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Users abandon a 12-field signup form. The likely fix is…",o:["add more fields","cut to the essentials","bigger title","more colours"],a:1,e:"Friction kills completion — fewer fields means more finish."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Consistent spacing and alignment mainly create a sense of…",o:["chaos","order and trust","speed","danger"],a:1,e:"Visual consistency signals care and makes interfaces feel trustworthy."},{t:"Spatial",q:"A button blends into the background. To make it stand out, raise the…",o:["contrast","file size","word count","margins only"],a:0,e:"Higher contrast makes an element pop."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Users keep missing an important link. Before a full redesign, first check its…",o:["colour name","visibility and placement","file format","copyright"],a:1,e:"Often the fix is simply making it more visible or better placed."},{t:"Logic",q:"Fitts's Law predicts that a target is reached faster when it is…",o:["smaller and farther away","larger and closer to the starting position","the same size as nearby items","placed at the screen centre always"],a:1,e:"Acquisition time drops as target size grows and distance shrinks — size and proximity are the two levers."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Gestalt similarity says objects that share a visual quality — colour, shape, or size — are perceived as…",o:["different and separate","belonging to the same group","moving together","random"],a:1,e:"Similarity groups elements perceptually; designers use it deliberately to signal relationship between controls."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Eye-tracking studies show users scan web pages in an F-shaped pattern. For critical content to be seen, it should be positioned…",o:["at the bottom of the page","in the top banner and left column","dead centre always","in the bottom-right corner"],a:1,e:"The F-pattern reveals where eyes actually go — align important information with the natural reading path."},{t:"Logic",q:"Cognitive load in interface design refers to the…",o:["page file size in kilobytes","mental effort a user must expend to understand and operate the interface","number of colours used","count of fonts on screen"],a:1,e:"High cognitive load causes errors and frustration — good design offloads work from the user's working memory."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A dark pattern is a design technique that…",o:["uses dark colour schemes for readability","manipulates users into actions they would not otherwise choose","improves night-mode contrast","speeds page load"],a:1,e:"Dark patterns exploit design power to serve the business at the user's expense — an ethical failure."},{t:"Logic",q:"Hick's Law predicts that decision time increases as the number of…",o:["colours in the palette grows","options presented to the user grows","fonts decreases","simultaneous users increases"],a:1,e:"More choices mean longer deliberation — streamlined menus and fewer options speed interaction."},{t:"Pattern",q:"A mental model is the user's internal belief about how a system works. Interface design is most learnable when it…",o:["surprises users with novel interactions","matches the user's existing mental model","replaces old models with jargon","maximises the number of new concepts"],a:1,e:"Matching the mental model reduces errors and the learning curve — the interface feels obvious, not foreign."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Jobs-to-be-done thinking focuses designers on…",o:["building feature lists from competitor analysis","the underlying goal the user is trying to achieve when they reach for the product","visual polish above function","reducing engineering scope"],a:1,e:"People hire products to get a job done — designing around the job yields solutions competitors rarely copy."},{t:"Spatial",q:"A layout with strong visual hierarchy steers the viewer's eye from…",o:["bottom to top","the most to the least important element","right to left by default","the fastest to the slowest element"],a:1,e:"Size, weight and contrast create a deliberate reading order — hierarchy prevents the eye from wandering randomly."},{t:"Logic",q:"Progressive disclosure presents only what the user needs right now, revealing further complexity…",o:["never — simplicity is absolute","on demand as the user signals readiness for it","randomly at set intervals","all at once after login"],a:1,e:"Staged revelation keeps the initial view clean while preserving access to power features for those who need them."},{t:"Lateral",q:"An A/B test run on 20 visitors shows button colour B outperforms A by 15%. The reliable conclusion is…",o:["B is the definitive winner — ship it","the sample is too small — the result is dominated by noise","A should be abandoned","colour is never significant"],a:1,e:"Small samples produce results that are mostly random variation — meaningful tests need hundreds or thousands of users."},{t:"Logic",q:"An affordance is a design property that…",o:["adds decorative texture","signals to the user how the element can be interacted with","stores user data","increases page weight"],a:1,e:"A door handle shaped to be pulled affords pulling — affordances communicate action without a single word of instruction."},{t:"Pattern",q:"The Gestalt principle of closure means users tend to…",o:["close browser tabs when confused","mentally complete incomplete shapes to perceive a whole familiar form","prefer enclosed rectangular layouts","dislike white space"],a:1,e:"Closure: the brain fills gaps to perceive a complete shape — used in logos and icon design deliberately."},{t:"Logic",q:"Red and green together are inaccessible to roughly 8% of males. Colour-only status indicators therefore…",o:["are always sufficient","must be supplemented with shape, label, or pattern to convey meaning","only affect dark-mode users","are a minor issue"],a:1,e:"WCAG accessibility standards require colour to never be the sole means of conveying critical information."},{t:"Spatial",q:"The 60-30-10 colour rule structures a palette as dominant, secondary, and accent in proportions…",o:["50-40-10","60-30-10","70-20-10","40-40-20"],a:1,e:"60% dominant sets the tone, 30% secondary supports it, 10% accent draws the eye — a balanced visual composition."},{t:"Lateral",q:"The double-diamond design process first diverges to explore broadly, then converges to define the problem, then diverges again to generate solutions, then converges to deliver. The key insight is that…",o:["solutions should be designed first, then validated","defining the right problem and solving it well are two separate creative acts","divergence is wasteful in professional settings","prototyping replaces the first diamond"],a:1,e:"Diverge-converge twice: premature solution-jumping skips problem definition and produces the wrong answer very efficiently."},{t:"Logic",q:"Microinteractions — hover states, loading indicators, confirmation animations — primarily serve to…",o:["slow users down","give immediate feedback so users know the system received and processed their action","add personality without function","increase perceived page weight"],a:1,e:"Feedback closes the interaction loop — without it, users resubmit forms, double-click buttons, and grow anxious."},{t:"Pattern",q:"The serial position effect means items placed at the beginning and end of a list are remembered better than those in the middle. For navigation menus, the most important links should be…",o:["buried in the middle","at the first and last positions","randomly distributed",'hidden behind a "more" menu'],a:1,e:"Primacy and recency: leverage the natural memory advantage of first and last positions for the highest-priority items."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Observing users working in their own real environment — rather than a lab — is called…",o:["a focus group","contextual inquiry","a heuristic evaluation","card sorting"],a:1,e:"Contextual inquiry captures authentic behaviour in context — lab studies capture what people do when watched in an unfamiliar room."}]},{id:"engineer",name:"Engineer",icon:"⚙️",color:"var(--leaf)",blurb:"Systems, trade-offs and failure analysis.",questions:[{t:"Logic",q:"A bridge is rated for 10 tonnes. A safety factor of 3 means it should actually withstand about…",o:["3 tonnes","10 tonnes","30 tonnes","100 tonnes"],a:2,e:"A safety factor multiplies the rating: 10 × 3 = 30 tonnes before failure."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A machine fails only on very hot afternoons. The smartest first hypothesis is…",o:["bad luck","heat-related expansion or cooling","the operator","the colour"],a:1,e:"A condition that tracks temperature points to thermal causes, not chance."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A gear turns at 100 rpm. A second gear with twice the teeth turns at…",o:["25 rpm","50 rpm","100 rpm","200 rpm"],a:1,e:"Twice the teeth means half the speed: 50 rpm."},{t:"Logic",q:"Two designs meet the spec; one uses half the parts. All else equal, prefer…",o:["the complex one","the simpler one","either","the heavier one"],a:1,e:"Fewer parts means fewer failure points and lower cost — simplicity wins."},{t:"Spatial",q:"A triangle is the strongest simple frame shape because it…",o:["looks nice","cannot deform without changing side lengths","is light","has three sides"],a:1,e:"Triangles are rigid: you cannot change their angles without stretching a side."},{t:"Logic",q:"A chain is only as strong as its…",o:["longest link","weakest link","first link","colour"],a:1,e:"Failure starts at the weakest point — that sets the system limit."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A prototype works but overheats. Best next move?",o:["ship it anyway","find and fix the heat source","paint it","ignore it"],a:1,e:"Address the root cause before release, not the symptom."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A pump fills a tank in 4 hours. Two identical pumps together take about…",o:["8 hours","4 hours","2 hours","1 hour"],a:2,e:"Two pumps do double the work — half the time, 2 hours."},{t:"Logic",q:"A part fails under heavy load but not light load. The issue is its…",o:["colour","strength or capacity limit","name","manufacture date"],a:1,e:"Failure under load points to a strength limit."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A safety factor of 2 means the design can hold about… the expected load.",o:["half","the same as","twice","ten times"],a:2,e:"A factor of 2 means twice the expected load."},{t:"Logic",q:"Two components connected in series (each 90% reliable) give a combined system reliability of about…",o:["90%","81%","99%","45%"],a:1,e:"Series reliability multiplies: 0.9 × 0.9 = 0.81. Every added series component reduces overall reliability."},{t:"Logic",q:"Two identical components wired in parallel (each 90% reliable) give a combined reliability of about…",o:["81%","90%","99%","45%"],a:2,e:"Parallel: 1 − (0.1 × 0.1) = 99%. Redundancy dramatically boosts reliability compared with series configuration."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A metal shaft fractures after millions of rotation cycles — well below its static breaking load. The failure mode is…",o:["corrosion fatigue","fatigue failure from cyclic stress accumulation","creep deformation","brittle fracture under impact"],a:1,e:"Fatigue: each cycle advances microscopic cracks until sudden fracture — without warning, far below the static limit."},{t:"Logic",q:"FMEA (Failure Mode and Effects Analysis) is a systematic method for…",o:["scheduling maintenance visits","identifying potential failure modes before they occur and ranking them by risk","testing software code","writing engineering reports"],a:1,e:"FMEA maps what could break, how likely it is, and what the consequence would be — so mitigation can be prioritised."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A system costs ₦4 million to install and saves ₦800,000 per year in operating costs. The simple payback period is…",o:["2 years","5 years","8 years","10 years"],a:1,e:"₦4M ÷ ₦800k/yr = 5 years to recover the installation cost through savings."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A footbridge vibrates violently when pedestrians walk across it in step. The most likely cause is…",o:["excessive weight on the spans","resonance — the step frequency matches the bridge's natural frequency","poor foundation soil","thermal expansion"],a:1,e:"Resonance amplifies oscillation when excitation frequency matches natural frequency — even modest forces become catastrophic."},{t:"Logic",q:"Creep is the gradual permanent deformation of a material caused by…",o:["sudden heavy impact","sustained load, especially at elevated temperature over time","zero loading in storage","wet or humid conditions"],a:1,e:"Creep governs design of high-temperature components — turbine blades, boiler tubes — where metal slowly elongates under load."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Negative feedback in a control loop acts to…",o:["amplify any deviation from the setpoint","reduce the difference between actual output and desired setpoint, stabilising the system","create resonance","always overshoot and oscillate"],a:1,e:"Negative feedback subtracts the error from the input signal — the output is pulled back toward the target continuously."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A centrifugal pump delivers 400 litres per minute. Filling a 12,000-litre storage tank takes…",o:["15 min","30 min","40 min","60 min"],a:1,e:"12,000 ÷ 400 = 30 minutes at the rated flow rate."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Specifying a material with twice the yield strength does not automatically double resistance to fatigue because…",o:["yield and fatigue strength always scale together","fatigue life depends on surface finish, stress concentration, and cyclic range — not yield strength alone","materials are never tested for fatigue","twice the yield is always more than enough"],a:1,e:"Fatigue cracks initiate at stress concentrations — a mirror-polished low-yield steel can outlast a rough high-yield one."},{t:"Logic",q:"The Pareto principle applied to engineering failures suggests that roughly 80% of failures originate from…",o:["every component equally","approximately 20% of causes","half the components","random, unpredictable sources"],a:1,e:"Focus resources on the vital few failure causes — fixing the top 20% of sources eliminates most incidents."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A cantilever beam carries a point load at its tip. Moving that load to twice the distance from the fixed support multiplies the bending moment at the root by…",o:["the same — distance doesn't matter","two times","four times","eight times"],a:1,e:"Bending moment = force × distance. Double the distance, double the moment. The root must withstand it all."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Life-cycle cost analysis selects designs based on the total cost across…",o:["purchase price alone","acquisition, installation, operation, maintenance, and end-of-life disposal","the first five years only","labour costs only"],a:1,e:"The cheapest to buy is often the most expensive to own — operating and maintenance costs frequently dominate."},{t:"Logic",q:"Von Mises stress is used to determine whether a material will yield under…",o:["temperature change alone","a combined multi-axis stress state — not just a single direction of load","impact loading only","fatigue cycling only"],a:1,e:"Von Mises combines all stress components into a single equivalent — compared against the uniaxial yield stress."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A pressure vessel designed for 8 bar is typically hydrostatically tested at…",o:["8 bar","10–12 bar (1.25–1.5× design pressure)","4 bar","80 bar"],a:1,e:"Hydrostatic proof tests at 1.25–1.5× design pressure verify structural integrity with a water-filled, low-energy medium."},{t:"Logic",q:"Galvanic corrosion accelerates when two dissimilar metals are placed in electrical contact inside…",o:["a vacuum","an electrolyte such as saltwater or moist concrete","dry air only","an insulated enclosure"],a:1,e:"The less noble metal becomes the anode and corrodes preferentially — prevented by isolation, coatings, or sacrificial anodes."},{t:"Pattern",q:"A Weibull distribution is used in reliability engineering to model…",o:["profit distribution","time-to-failure across infant mortality, random failure, and wear-out phases","material colour degradation","team performance curves"],a:1,e:"The Weibull shape parameter beta identifies the failure phase — below 1 early-life, 1 random, above 1 wear-out."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A stress concentration factor Kt at a notch or hole means the local peak stress is…",o:["lower than the nominal stress — the geometry distributes load","higher than nominal stress by a factor of Kt","identical to the nominal stress","zero at the notch tip"],a:1,e:"Stress concentrations are where fatigue cracks and fracture initiate — sharp corners can multiply stress several times over."},{t:"Logic",q:"A cold-standby redundant component does not accumulate wear or fatigue until it is switched into service. This makes it preferable to active parallel redundancy when…",o:["cost is unlimited","minimising cumulative exposure and component ageing matters most","the primary component is new","weight is irrelevant"],a:1,e:"Cold standby components age only after activation — their reliability at the moment of need is closer to new."}]},{id:"teacher",name:"Teacher",icon:"📚",color:"var(--grape)",blurb:"Sequencing, diagnosis and clear explanation.",questions:[{t:"Logic",q:'A student gets every "carry" subtraction wrong but simple ones right. The gap is most likely…',o:["laziness","the borrowing step","eyesight","the pencil"],a:1,e:"The error clusters on one concept — borrowing — so that is what to reteach."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Half the class fails one question. Best first response is to…",o:["blame the class","re-examine how it was taught","ignore it","lower the grade"],a:1,e:"A shared failure usually signals the explanation, not the students."},{t:"Pattern",q:"To teach a hard idea, the usual order is…",o:["abstract → example","example → abstract rule","test → teach","random"],a:1,e:"Concrete examples first build intuition before the general rule."},{t:"Verbal",q:"Which feedback helps a learner most?",o:['"Wrong."','"Good job!"','"Close — check step 2"','"Try harder"'],a:2,e:"Specific, actionable feedback points to exactly what to fix."},{t:"Logic",q:"A quiz where everyone scores 100% mainly tells you it was…",o:["a great class","possibly too easy to distinguish","badly marked","unfair"],a:1,e:"If it cannot separate levels of understanding, it may have been too easy."},{t:"Logic",q:"A student recites a rule but cannot use it. They likely have…",o:["mastery","memorised it without understanding","a discipline issue","perfect grasp"],a:1,e:"Recall without application signals shallow, rote learning."},{t:"Verbal",q:"The clearest learning objective starts with…",o:['"understand stuff"','an action verb like "calculate"','"know things"','"be smart"'],a:1,e:"Measurable verbs make objectives clear and assessable."},{t:"Lateral",q:"One method bores fast learners but suits slow ones. The fix is to…",o:["pick one forever","differentiate / offer extensions","remove slow ones","always go faster"],a:1,e:"Different paces need different paths — differentiation serves both."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Most of a class fails the same question. The likely problem is…",o:["the whole class","how that idea was taught","the room","the date"],a:1,e:"A shared gap usually points to the explanation, not the students."},{t:"Logic",q:"A student learns best by doing. The best lesson gives them more…",o:["lectures","hands-on practice","silence","tests only"],a:1,e:"Active practice suits a hands-on learner."},{t:"Logic",q:`Bloom's Taxonomy places "analyse" above "apply" because analysis requires…`,o:["less thinking than applying a method","breaking material apart and examining relationships — not just executing a procedure","memorising more content","repeating a skill faster"],a:1,e:"Bloom's hierarchy: remember → understand → apply → analyse → evaluate → create. Each level subsumes the one below."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Formative assessment differs from summative assessment in that its primary purpose is…",o:["assigning a final grade","informing and adjusting instruction while learning is still in progress","measuring accountability to parents","ranking students against each other"],a:1,e:"Formative is assessment for learning; summative is assessment of learning — purpose, timing, and use are all different."},{t:"Logic",q:"Vygotsky's Zone of Proximal Development is the gap between what a learner can do independently and what they can do…",o:["in a test environment","with guidance from a more capable person","in a different subject","after a long holiday"],a:1,e:"Teaching in the ZPD is most efficient — not below the learner (boring) nor beyond reach (frustrating), but at the productive edge."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Dweck's growth mindset treats failure as…",o:["evidence of fixed innate ability","useful feedback and a natural part of developing skill","a reason to avoid challenging tasks","proof that effort is pointless"],a:1,e:"Growth mindset: ability develops through effort and strategy. Fixed mindset: ability is static. The belief shapes the behaviour."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Retrieval practice (self-testing) improves long-term retention more than re-reading because…",o:["it wastes less time overall","actively reconstructing memory from scratch strengthens the memory trace more than passive review","re-reading never helps","tests increase anxiety productively"],a:1,e:"The testing effect: the effort of retrieving, not the act of reviewing, is what consolidates durable memory."},{t:"Logic",q:"Interleaving practice — mixing different topics or problem types in one session — feels harder but produces…",o:["worse long-term retention than blocked practice","stronger retention and ability to transfer learning to new situations","the same results as blocked practice","burnout in learners"],a:1,e:"Interleaving forces the brain to discriminate between problem types — harder during training, far better at transfer."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Desirable difficulties are learning conditions that…",o:["make learning impossible for most students","slow initial acquisition but produce stronger, more durable long-term memory","feel easy and natural","should be avoided in professional training"],a:1,e:"Spacing, interleaving, and testing feel harder — learners often believe they are working less well — yet retention months later is superior."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Backward design (Understanding by Design) starts curriculum planning with…",o:["the first lesson topic in the textbook","the desired learning outcomes and evidence of achievement — then working backward to plan activities","the most engaging activity first","the room layout and timetable"],a:1,e:"Starting with the goal prevents activities being chosen by habit — everything is selected to serve the intended outcome."},{t:"Logic",q:"Research on wait time shows that pausing 3–5 seconds after asking a question before accepting answers…",o:["wastes instructional time","increases the number of students who respond and improves the quality and depth of answers","benefits only advanced students","reduces engagement"],a:1,e:"Extended wait time allows more students to form a complete thought — particularly benefiting slower processors and second-language learners."},{t:"Verbal",q:"Scaffolding in education refers to temporary instructional support that is gradually…",o:["made permanent in the curriculum","removed as the learner gains competence and can work independently","replaced by stricter grading","assessed on a rubric"],a:1,e:"Scaffolding bridges the ZPD — present when needed, faded as mastery grows, gone when the learner no longer needs it."},{t:"Logic",q:`The apex level of Bloom's revised taxonomy — "create" — requires learners to…`,o:["list facts from memory","generate something new by combining knowledge and skills in an original way","judge quality using criteria","apply a given procedure"],a:1,e:"Create sits above evaluate: producing a new essay, design, or experiment — not just assessing or applying existing knowledge."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Spaced repetition schedules review sessions at increasing intervals, timed to fall…",o:["at random moments throughout the term","just before the memory trace fades — the point of maximum efficiency","every single day without variation","only during exam revision"],a:1,e:"Reviewing at the edge of forgetting maximises memory consolidation per session — Ebbinghaus's forgetting curve applied."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Transfer of learning from training to a new context is hardest when the training and application conditions are…",o:["varied and unpredictable","highly similar to each other","deliberately challenging","very different from each other"],a:3,e:"Near transfer: similar contexts. Far transfer: very different contexts — achieved through varied practice, not similarity."},{t:"Logic",q:"The expertise reversal effect occurs when instructional support that helps novices learn…",o:["remains equally helpful for experts","becomes redundant or even interfering for experts who no longer need it","reduces expert performance only in mathematics","always improves outcomes at all levels"],a:1,e:"Experts have efficient schemas — guidance that fills gaps for novices clutters and slows expert processing."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Near-peer teaching — students explaining to classmates slightly behind them — can be highly effective because peers…",o:["are always more knowledgeable than teachers","explain in language closer to where the learner currently is, reducing abstraction gaps","never make conceptual errors","reduce the teacher's workload"],a:1,e:`Near-peer explanations hit the right level of abstraction — an expert's "obvious" step is a novice's invisible leap.`},{t:"Logic",q:"Criterion-referenced assessment judges a student's performance against…",o:["the class average score","a fixed, pre-defined standard of what they should be able to do","last year's cohort results","the most able student in the group"],a:1,e:"Criterion-referenced: did you meet the standard? Norm-referenced: how do you rank? They serve very different purposes."},{t:"Verbal",q:"A flipped classroom reverses the traditional model by moving direct instruction…",o:["to after the exam period","out of class time — via video or reading — freeing class time for practice and application","to a specialist teacher","to a later year"],a:1,e:"Flipped learning reserves face-to-face time — the most scarce and interactive resource — for doing, not watching."},{t:"Lateral",q:"High-stakes testing narrows curriculum because rational teachers focus instructional time on…",o:["broad creative skills","what will be tested, crowding out subjects and skills that are not assessed","all subjects equally","the weakest students only"],a:1,e:"Teaching to the test is a predictable system response to high-stakes accountability — a policy design problem, not a teacher character flaw."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Self-explanation — asking learners to articulate their reasoning aloud or in writing — improves learning by…",o:["reducing the need for teacher feedback","revealing gaps in understanding and forcing integration of new information with existing knowledge","slowing overall lesson pace","replacing practice exercises"],a:1,e:"Self-explaining surfaces what is understood and what is not — the act of putting it into words forces elaboration."},{t:"Logic",q:"Epistemic curiosity — the drive to resolve knowledge gaps — is most reliably triggered in learners by…",o:["giving them all the answers upfront","exposing them to an interesting gap between what they know and what they want to understand","increasing the difficulty without support","reducing class time"],a:1,e:"Curiosity follows the gap: learners need to know enough to know they don't know enough — then it becomes compelling."}]},{id:"nurse",name:"Nurse",icon:"💊",color:"var(--berry)",blurb:"Prioritising, dosage and patient reasoning.",questions:[{t:"Lateral",q:"Four patients arrive at once. Who is seen first?",o:["the loudest","the one struggling to breathe","first to arrive","the calmest"],a:1,e:"Triage treats the most life-threatening problem first — breathing comes before comfort."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A dose is 5 mg per 10 kg of weight. A 30 kg child needs…",o:["5 mg","10 mg","15 mg","30 mg"],a:2,e:"30 kg is three lots of 10 kg → 3 × 5 = 15 mg."},{t:"Logic",q:'A patient says they took "the blue pill twice." Before acting you should…',o:["assume the dose","clarify which pill and how much","ignore it","double it"],a:1,e:"Ambiguity around medication is resolved by confirming exact drug and amount."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Medication is due every 6 hours. If the last dose was at 08:00, the next is at…",o:["12:00","14:00","16:00","20:00"],a:1,e:"08:00 + 6 hours = 14:00."},{t:"Logic",q:"A reading looks abnormal but the patient feels fine and looks well. You should…",o:["panic","recheck the reading/equipment","ignore the patient","discharge them"],a:1,e:"When data and the whole picture disagree, verify the measurement before acting."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Target is 2,000 ml a day. By noon a patient has had 800 ml. Remaining is…",o:["800 ml","1,200 ml","2,000 ml","200 ml"],a:1,e:"2,000 − 800 = 1,200 ml left."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Before giving medication, the safest habit is checking the…",o:["clock only","right patient, drug, dose, route, time","colour","label font"],a:1,e:'The "five rights" prevent the most common medication errors.'},{t:"Logic",q:"A monitor alarms constantly for tiny changes. The risk is that staff…",o:["respond faster","start ignoring real alarms","feel calmer","sleep better"],a:1,e:"Alarm fatigue makes people tune out — including genuine emergencies."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A patient's readings look normal but they seem unwell. You should…",o:["trust only the numbers","look closer and reassess","ignore it","go off shift"],a:1,e:"Clinical signs matter even when numbers seem fine."},{t:"Logic",q:"Two patients need help at once — one in danger, one stable. You attend…",o:["the stable one","the one in danger first","neither","at random"],a:1,e:"Triage treats the most urgent need first."},{t:"Verbal",q:"The SBAR communication tool stands for Situation, Background, Assessment, and…",o:["Report","Recommendation","Result","Record"],a:1,e:"The Recommendation step ensures the handover includes a clear ask — not just data, but a proposed action."},{t:"Logic",q:"The most effective intervention for preventing pressure ulcers in bed-bound patients is…",o:["nutritional supplements alone","regular repositioning every two hours to relieve sustained pressure on bony prominences","extra pillows under the head","prescribing anti-inflammatory drugs"],a:1,e:"Sustained pressure collapses capillaries — repositioning every two hours breaks the ischaemic cycle before tissue dies."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A patient must drink 2.5 litres today and has consumed 1.6 litres by 15:00. Volume remaining is…",o:["500 ml","900 ml","1.6 litres","1 litre"],a:1,e:"2,500 − 1,600 = 900 ml still to drink before the day ends."},{t:"Logic",q:"Capillary refill time of more than 2 seconds after pressing a fingernail bed suggests…",o:["normal peripheral circulation","potentially poor peripheral perfusion — a marker for shock or dehydration","healthy hydration","a normal finding in cold weather only"],a:1,e:"Slow refill indicates sluggish blood return to the periphery — a prompt for full assessment of circulation and fluid status."},{t:"Pattern",q:"SIRS (Systemic Inflammatory Response Syndrome) criteria for suspected sepsis include fever or hypothermia, tachycardia, tachypnoea, and…",o:["normal white cell count","abnormal white cell count — raised or critically low","low blood pressure alone as the sole trigger","normal respiratory rate"],a:1,e:"Two or more SIRS criteria with suspected infection trigger sepsis workup — abnormal WBC is one of the four core markers."},{t:"Lateral",q:"An adult patient with full mental capacity refuses a blood transfusion that the medical team believes is lifesaving. The nurse's legal and ethical duty is to…",o:["override the refusal and administer the transfusion","respect the decision, ensure full information was given, document it, and notify the team","ask the family to override","withhold all other care"],a:1,e:"Autonomy of a capacitous adult is paramount — the right to refuse even lifesaving treatment is absolute in law."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A blood potassium result of 6.4 mEq/L is…",o:["at the lower limit of normal","dangerously elevated — hyperkalaemia requiring urgent action","normal for elderly patients","mildly below normal"],a:1,e:"Normal K+ is 3.5–5.0 mEq/L. Above 6.0 risks fatal ventricular arrhythmia — treat without delay."},{t:"Logic",q:"A DNR (Do Not Resuscitate) order applies specifically to…",o:["all medical treatment in the patient's care","cardiopulmonary resuscitation in the event of cardiac or respiratory arrest only","administration of analgesia","fluid management decisions"],a:1,e:"A DNR is not a withdrawal of care — antibiotics, fluids, analgesia, and comfort measures all continue unless separately addressed."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A prescribed dose was not given because ward stock had run out. The correct immediate actions are to…",o:["skip the dose and say nothing until handover","document the omission, report it, chase the pharmacy urgently, and monitor the patient","give the nearest alternative drug without checking","wait until the next scheduled dose time"],a:1,e:"Medication omissions are reportable clinical incidents — silent gaps in prescribed therapy can cause serious patient harm."},{t:"Numbers",q:"An IV infusion of 750 ml must run over 6 hours. The correct flow rate is…",o:["100 ml/h","125 ml/h","150 ml/h","200 ml/h"],a:1,e:"750 ÷ 6 = 125 ml/h. Setting the pump correctly is a safety-critical calculation."},{t:"Pattern",q:"NEWS2 (National Early Warning Score 2) is designed to help nursing staff…",o:["plan discharge timing","detect physiological deterioration early by aggregating vital sign trends into a single score","calculate drug doses","organise ward rounds"],a:1,e:"Rising NEWS2 triggers escalation protocols — it catches subtle multi-sign deterioration that single readings might miss."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A patient weighs 70 kg and requires a drug at 3 mcg/kg/min. The required rate is…",o:["70 mcg/min","210 mcg/min","3 mcg/min","21 mcg/min"],a:1,e:"70 × 3 = 210 mcg/min. Weight-based dosing must be recalculated precisely — rounding errors are harmful."},{t:"Logic",q:"Informed consent for a procedure requires the patient to understand…",o:["the nurse's qualifications","the nature of the procedure, its material risks, its expected benefits, and available alternatives","the hospital's billing policy","the surgical instrument list"],a:1,e:"Consent without adequate information about risk and alternatives is not legally or ethically valid — it is just agreement."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A patient with metabolic acidosis has a raised anion gap. Likely causes include…",o:["vomiting of gastric acid","diabetic ketoacidosis, lactic acidosis, or toxic ingestion — not simple diarrhoea or vomiting","diarrhoea causing bicarbonate loss","respiratory problems causing CO₂ retention"],a:1,e:"Raised anion gap signals unmeasured anions — ketones, lactate, or toxins consuming bicarbonate buffer."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Hypoactive delirium in elderly patients is frequently missed because it presents as…",o:["shouting and pulling at lines","quiet withdrawal, reduced responsiveness, and confusion — easily mistaken for tiredness or depression","worsening pain scores","elevated blood pressure"],a:1,e:"Hypoactive delirium kills quietly — unlike agitated delirium, it does not demand attention but still signals critical deterioration."},{t:"Logic",q:"The priority actions in the Hour-1 sepsis bundle include measuring serum lactate, taking blood cultures, giving broad-spectrum antibiotics, and for hypotension…",o:["waiting 4 hours to reassess","administering 30 ml/kg IV crystalloid fluid and monitoring urine output","reducing the IV line site","ordering a CT scan first"],a:1,e:"The 1-hour bundle is time-critical — each hour of delayed antibiotics in sepsis significantly worsens mortality."},{t:"Logic",q:"A patient's Glasgow Coma Scale falls from 15 to 10 over two hours. This warrants…",o:["a note at the next handover only","immediate escalation to medical staff — a fall of 2 or more is a significant deterioration","re-assessment in two more hours","repositioning and observation only"],a:1,e:"GCS drop of 2 or more is a clinical emergency criterion in most early warning systems — act before it falls further."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Intravenous potassium given peripherally must not exceed a rate of approximately…",o:["40 mEq/h","10 mEq/h","100 mEq/h","1 mEq/h"],a:1,e:"Rates above 10–20 mEq/h peripherally cause vein pain and risk cardiac arrhythmia — central line or slower rate required for higher doses."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A patient on warfarin has an INR of 6.2 against a target of 2–3. The immediate clinical priority is…",o:["re-checking the target range with the prescriber","identifying and managing serious bleeding risk — the coagulation system is dangerously overridden","doubling the next warfarin dose","no urgency — review at the next clinic visit"],a:1,e:"INR 6 means clotting is massively impaired — major spontaneous bleeding is a real and immediate risk requiring urgent reversal."},{t:"Logic",q:"An advance directive (living will) allows a person to…",o:["transfer property before death","set out legally binding decisions about future medical treatment in case they lose decision-making capacity","appoint a next of kin only","grant power of attorney for finances"],a:1,e:"Advance directives exercise prospective autonomy — honouring them is a legal and ethical obligation even if the patient can no longer speak."}]},{id:"founder",name:"Entrepreneur",icon:"🚀",color:"var(--lantern)",blurb:"Decisions under uncertainty and trade-offs.",questions:[{t:"Lateral",q:"A new feature took 3 months and nobody uses it. The healthiest view is…",o:["build more of it","treat the 3 months as a sunk cost and move on","blame users","hide the data"],a:1,e:"Past effort is sunk; decisions should look forward, not chase what is already spent."},{t:"Numbers",q:"You earn ₦400 per sale and spend ₦100 to get each customer. Profit per sale is…",o:["₦100","₦300","₦400","₦500"],a:1,e:"₦400 earned − ₦100 to acquire = ₦300 profit per sale."},{t:"Logic",q:"Two markets: one huge but crowded, one small but empty. For a tiny new team, often best to…",o:["fight the crowd","start in the small open niche","do both","do neither"],a:1,e:"A focused beachhead is winnable; competing everywhere spreads a small team too thin."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Five friends love your product. Before scaling you most need to know…",o:["the logo colour","whether strangers will pay too","your office size","a fancy name"],a:1,e:"Friends are biased; real validation is paying customers who do not know you."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Revenue grows 10% each month. After about how many months does it roughly double?",o:["2","7","12","20"],a:1,e:'At ~10% monthly growth it doubles in roughly 7 months (the "rule of 70": 70 ÷ 10).'},{t:"Lateral",q:`Everyone says they'd "definitely buy" yet nobody pre-orders. Trust…`,o:["the words","the behaviour (no orders)","neither","the loudest"],a:1,e:"Stated intent is cheap; paying behaviour is the real signal."},{t:"Numbers",q:"You keep ₦200 profit per customer but spend ₦600 to get one. This is…",o:["profitable","losing money per customer","break-even","great"],a:1,e:"Spending ₦600 to earn ₦200 loses ₦400 each time — unsustainable."},{t:"Logic",q:"A feature doubles signups but triples costs. Keeping it depends on…",o:["the colour","whether new users are worth more than the added cost","the name","the season"],a:1,e:"Growth only helps if user value exceeds the cost to serve them."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Lots of signups but few keep using the product. The real problem is…",o:["marketing","retention — value delivered","the logo","the office"],a:1,e:"Sign-ups without retention means the product is not delivering lasting value."},{t:"Numbers",q:"You spend ₦5,000 to win a customer worth ₦3,000. This is…",o:["profitable","losing money per customer","free","doubling money"],a:1,e:"Paying more to acquire than a customer is worth loses money."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Your company has ₦6 million in the bank and spends ₦750,000 per month. Your runway is…",o:["6 months","8 months","10 months","12 months"],a:1,e:"₦6M ÷ ₦750k/month = 8 months of runway before cash runs out."},{t:"Logic",q:"Cohort analysis groups users by when they signed up in order to…",o:["sort customers alphabetically","track how each batch behaves over time — revealing whether the product is improving or degrading for new users","identify the biggest spenders","simplify the support queue"],a:1,e:"Cohort analysis separates time-of-signup effects — a recent cohort retaining better signals a real product improvement."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Customer Lifetime Value is ₦18,000 and Customer Acquisition Cost is ₦4,500. The LTV:CAC ratio is…",o:["2:1","4:1","6:1","1:4"],a:1,e:"₦18,000 ÷ ₦4,500 = 4. A ratio of 3:1 or higher is generally considered healthy for a sustainable business."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A network effect means each additional user…",o:["raises the server cost proportionally","makes the product more valuable for every existing user","reduces product quality","forces a price increase"],a:1,e:"Network effects create compounding value and powerful competitive moats — the product gets better as it grows."},{t:"Pattern",q:`Geoffrey Moore's "crossing the chasm" describes the gap between visionary early adopters and…`,o:["international markets","the pragmatic early majority mainstream — the hardest and most critical transition","enterprise accounts","investors seeking returns"],a:1,e:"Early adopters tolerate rough edges; the mainstream demands proven, complete solutions — the chasm kills most startups."},{t:"Logic",q:"A business with mostly fixed costs and low variable costs has high operating leverage, meaning…",o:["it cannot scale","incremental revenue above breakeven flows largely to profit — but losses below it are equally amplified","variable costs dominate margins","growth requires proportional headcount"],a:1,e:"High operating leverage is a double-edged sword: great margins when growing, painful losses when revenue falls short."},{t:"Pattern",q:"An S-curve in technology adoption shows slow early take-up, then rapid acceleration through the mainstream, then…",o:["continued exponential growth","plateau as the addressable market saturates","sudden collapse","a return to slow growth"],a:1,e:"S-curves are universal in adoption — recognising where you are on the curve shapes product, pricing, and competition strategy."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Value-based pricing sets price according to…",o:["the cost to produce the product plus a standard margin","how much the customer values the outcome delivered — their willingness to pay","the average competitor price in the market","the founder's gut feeling about fairness"],a:1,e:"Value-based pricing captures more of the value created — cost-plus leaves surplus on the table."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Burn multiple = total cash burned ÷ net new ARR added in the same period. A burn multiple of 5 means the company spent ₦5 for every ₦1 of new recurring revenue. This indicates…",o:["very efficient growth","highly inefficient growth — most healthy companies target below 2","the company is profitable","burn rate equals revenue"],a:1,e:"Burn multiple is an efficiency metric — lower is better. Below 1 is elite; above 2 warrants scrutiny."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Monthly churn is 8%. After 3 months, approximately what fraction of the original cohort remains?",o:["76%","70%","92%","80%"],a:1,e:"0.92 × 0.92 × 0.92 ≈ 0.78 — roughly 78%, closest to 70% among the options given."},{t:"Logic",q:"Clayton Christensen's innovator's dilemma describes how incumbents fail because rational decisions to serve their best customers lead them to…",o:["overspend on R&D","ignore the disruptive low-end entrant until it is too late to respond","hire the wrong people","cut prices prematurely"],a:1,e:"Good management at incumbents optimises for current profitable customers — exactly what blinds them to disruptive threats from below."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A product has a high Net Promoter Score but churn is rising simultaneously. The most likely explanation is…",o:["customers deeply love the product but are moving away by accident","users say positive things in surveys but are not finding sufficient value to stay — a signal-action gap","the NPS methodology is broken","both metrics are equally reliable"],a:1,e:"Behaviour trumps stated intention — divergence between NPS and churn demands investigation of actual retention drivers."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Monthly Recurring Revenue is ₦3 million. Annual Recurring Revenue is…",o:["₦3M","₦30M","₦36M","₦300M"],a:2,e:"ARR = MRR × 12 = ₦36M. ARR is the standard metric for SaaS business scale and investor valuation."},{t:"Logic",q:"The strongest evidence of genuine product-market fit is…",o:["high social media following","organic word-of-mouth growth and retention rates you did not engineer through discounts or campaigns","a large marketing budget generating growth","a signed letter of intent from a customer"],a:1,e:"Real PMF creates pull — users return, refer others, and express genuine loss when asked to imagine the product disappearing."},{t:"Lateral",q:'A startup that reaches "default alive" — covering costs from revenue — benefits primarily by…',o:["impressing investors with profitability","removing fundraising pressure and preserving the ability to make long-term decisions without a forced exit or down round","showing cost discipline only","limiting growth to avoid attention"],a:1,e:"Default alive buys time and agency — bad funding markets, difficult terms, and strategic pivots all become navigable."},{t:"Pattern",q:'A "land and expand" enterprise sales motion deliberately starts with a small initial deal to…',o:["limit revenue risk","establish a foothold, then grow within the account as proven value earns more budget and users","avoid enterprise procurement complexity","reduce the cost of sales"],a:1,e:"Expansion revenue from existing accounts costs far less than new acquisition — the land-and-expand model targets high LTV."},{t:"Numbers",q:"SaaS quick ratio = (new MRR + expansion MRR) ÷ (churned MRR + contracted MRR). A quick ratio of 4 means the business is adding revenue…",o:["at breakeven with losses","four times faster than it is losing it — considered a strong growth signal","at the same rate as churn","too slowly to cover costs"],a:1,e:"Quick ratio above 4 shows excellent net revenue retention — each unit of lost revenue is outweighed four-to-one by gain."},{t:"Logic",q:"A regulatory moat protects a business by…",o:["making the product cheaper to build","requiring competitors to obtain licences, certifications, or regulatory approval that take years and significant capital","reducing the product's marginal cost","eliminating the need for sales effort"],a:1,e:"Compliance barriers raise the cost of entry for new competitors — even technically superior products face years of regulatory delay."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A SaaS company raises prices by 20% and sees churn barely move. This demonstrates…",o:["that customers are trapped with no alternatives","strong pricing power — customers value the product well above its previous price","the sales team is underperforming","the market is shrinking"],a:1,e:"Inelastic demand at higher prices is a rare and valuable signal — it reveals genuine willingness to pay beyond the old anchor."},{t:"Logic",q:"A pivot keeps the learning from validated experiments while changing…",o:["the founding team immediately","the strategy, business model, or target market that was not working","all existing code and infrastructure","the company name and branding"],a:1,e:"A pivot is disciplined — it is not a restart. Validated learning is the asset; the non-working hypothesis is what changes."}]},{id:"accountant",name:"Accountant",icon:"💰",color:"var(--leaf)",blurb:"Numbers, balance and audit logic.",questions:[{t:"Numbers",q:"Revenue is ₦500k and costs are ₦320k. Profit is…",o:["₦180k","₦220k","₦820k","₦320k"],a:0,e:"500 − 320 = ₦180k."},{t:"Logic",q:"Debits must equal credits, but they do not. That means…",o:["extra profit","a recording error","more cash","nothing"],a:1,e:"Unbalanced books signal an error to find."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Add 10% VAT to a ₦2,000 item. The total is…",o:["₦2,200","₦2,020","₦1,800","₦2,000"],a:0,e:"10% of 2,000 is 200, so ₦2,200."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Cash is high but profit is low. Most useful to check…",o:["the logo","when income and costs are recorded","staff names","the date"],a:1,e:"Cash and profit differ because of timing — accruals and unpaid bills."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Saving ₦5,000 every month, after one year you have…",o:["₦50,000","₦60,000","₦55,000","₦600,000"],a:1,e:"5,000 × 12 = ₦60,000."},{t:"Logic",q:"An expense accidentally recorded twice makes profit look…",o:["higher","lower","the same","zero"],a:1,e:"Double-counted costs cut into reported profit."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Buy at ₦800, sell at ₦1,000. The profit margin is…",o:["10%","20%","25%","80%"],a:1,e:"₦200 profit on a ₦1,000 sale is 20%."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Two months have identical sales but very different profit. First check…",o:["the colour","expenses that changed","the weather","the font"],a:1,e:"If sales match, the difference lives in the costs."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Assets are ₦900k and liabilities ₦400k. Owner's equity is…",o:["₦1,300k","₦500k","₦400k","₦900k"],a:1,e:"Equity = assets − liabilities = 900 − 400 = ₦500k."},{t:"Logic",q:"Profit is positive but the bank balance is falling. A likely reason is…",o:["too much cash","unpaid invoices or large purchases","nothing","more profit"],a:1,e:"Profit on paper can differ from cash when money is tied up."},{t:"Logic",q:"Accrual accounting records revenue when it is…",o:["received as cash in the bank","earned — when the service is delivered or goods transferred — regardless of when payment arrives","invoiced, even if disputed","estimated by management"],a:1,e:"Accrual basis matches income and expenses to the period they relate to — not to cash timing. This gives a truer picture of performance."},{t:"Logic",q:"Straight-line depreciation spreads the cost of an asset…",o:["front-loaded heavily in year one","evenly across the asset's useful life as equal annual charges","only when the asset is sold","based on actual usage each year"],a:1,e:"Annual charge = (cost − residual value) ÷ useful years. Simple and transparent, but not always economically realistic."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Days Sales Outstanding (DSO) = (accounts receivable ÷ annual revenue) × 365. A DSO of 75 means customers pay on average in…",o:["30 days","75 days","3 months","one week"],a:1,e:"DSO measures collection speed. 75 days means cash is tied up for over two months after invoicing — a cash flow concern."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A business switches from FIFO to LIFO inventory accounting during a period of rising input prices. Reported gross profit will…",o:["rise — older cheap stock is cleared first","fall — more expensive recent stock is charged to cost of sales first","stay the same","depend on sales volume alone"],a:1,e:"LIFO matches the latest, priciest costs against revenue — compressing reported margins during inflation."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Fixed costs are ₦200,000. Selling price per unit is ₦80 and variable cost per unit is ₦30. Break-even volume is…",o:["2,500 units","4,000 units","6,667 units","2,000 units"],a:1,e:"Break-even = ₦200k ÷ (₦80 − ₦30) = 200,000 ÷ 50 = 4,000 units."},{t:"Logic",q:"A deferred tax liability arises when tax authorities permit a deduction earlier than accounting standards allow, meaning the company will…",o:["never pay the tax","pay more tax in future years when the timing difference reverses","receive a tax refund later","have lower reported profit now"],a:1,e:"Accelerated tax depreciation versus slower accounting depreciation creates a temporary benefit — but the liability unwinds."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Goodwill appears on a company's balance sheet only when…",o:["the company is particularly well-known","it acquires another business for more than the fair value of its identifiable net assets","management decides to record it","the company is listed on a stock exchange"],a:1,e:"Internally generated goodwill is never recorded — it only appears in the acquired company's books through purchase accounting."},{t:"Logic",q:"Transfer pricing governs how transactions between related entities within a multinational group are priced because…",o:["it applies only to imported goods","pricing affects which jurisdiction reports the profit — and therefore where tax is paid","all jurisdictions use the same tax rate","it prevents currency risk"],a:1,e:"Inflated or deflated inter-company prices can shift profit to low-tax jurisdictions — tax authorities require arm's-length pricing."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Current ratio = current assets ÷ current liabilities. A ratio of 0.7 means…",o:["excellent liquidity — assets far exceed liabilities","current liabilities exceed current assets — a near-term cash risk worth investigating","the business is profitable","the ratio is above the safe threshold"],a:1,e:"A current ratio below 1 means liquid assets may not cover obligations due in the short term — a liquidity flag."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Inventory must be written down to net realisable value (NRV) when NRV is…",o:["above cost — recognising gains early","below cost — the lower of cost or NRV rule requires the loss to be recognised immediately","equal to cost — as a precaution","always — regardless of market price"],a:1,e:"The lower of cost or NRV principle is conservative — it prevents overstating inventory and future profits."},{t:"Logic",q:"An impairment review for goodwill compares the carrying value on the balance sheet against the…",o:["original purchase price","recoverable amount — the higher of value in use and fair value less costs to sell","replacement cost","nominal book value"],a:1,e:"Where carrying value exceeds recoverable amount, the difference is written off as an impairment loss — it cannot be reversed later."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A business with high fixed costs sees revenue rise 10% while fixed costs remain unchanged. Operating profit will rise by…",o:["exactly 10%","more than 10%","less than 10%","zero"],a:1,e:"High operating leverage: incremental revenue above breakeven mostly flows to profit — percentage profit growth exceeds percentage revenue growth."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Earnings management using legitimate accounting choices (estimates, timing) differs from fraud because it…",o:["always produces the same result as fraud","uses genuine discretion within accounting rules rather than fabricating or omitting facts","is always disclosed to auditors","is only done by small companies"],a:1,e:"Legal earnings management exploits rule-based flexibility; fraud involves misrepresentation. The ethical question is whether the picture is true and fair."},{t:"Logic",q:"A contingent liability is disclosed in the notes to the accounts (rather than recognised on the balance sheet) when it is…",o:["certain to crystallise","possible but not probable, or cannot be reliably measured","impossible under any scenario","already paid"],a:1,e:"Probable and measurable = recognise. Possible or uncertain = disclose. Remote = omit entirely."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Revenue is ₦15 million and EBITDA is ₦3 million. The EBITDA margin is…",o:["5%","20%","50%","45%"],a:1,e:"3 ÷ 15 = 0.20 = 20%. EBITDA margin strips out financing and accounting choices to show operating cash generation."},{t:"Logic",q:"The accounting principle of substance over form requires that transactions are recorded according to their…",o:["legal label and documentation","economic reality — even when that differs from the legal structure","invoice date","payment schedule"],a:1,e:"A sale that retains all risk with the seller may be economically a loan — substance governs accounting, not the contract title."},{t:"Lateral",q:'A "big bath" charge occurs when a new CEO records large one-time write-offs early in their tenure in order to…',o:["impress auditors with transparency","set a low earnings baseline that will be easier to beat in subsequent periods under their leadership","commit accounting fraud","comply with tax requirements"],a:1,e:"Big baths reset expectations downward — future performance looks better by comparison. Legal, but opportunistic."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Altman's Z-score model uses a combination of financial ratios to estimate the probability of…",o:["revenue growth","corporate financial distress or bankruptcy within two years","dividend sustainability","credit rating upgrades"],a:1,e:"Z-score below 1.81 signals distress; above 2.99 signals health. Banks and analysts use it as an early warning tool."},{t:"Logic",q:"The matching principle requires that expenses are recognised in the same period as…",o:["when they are paid in cash","the revenue they helped generate — not necessarily when cash changes hands","year-end by default","when invoiced by the supplier"],a:1,e:"Matching ensures the income statement reflects true economic performance of the period, not the accident of payment timing."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Year-end window dressing — such as temporarily repaying a revolving credit facility just before the balance sheet date — inflates the apparent…",o:["gross margin","current ratio and net debt — creating a misleadingly strong liquidity snapshot","long-term liabilities","revenue figure"],a:1,e:"Ratios taken at a single snapshot date can be manipulated by timing. Quarterly trend analysis exposes the pattern."}]},{id:"scientist",name:"Scientist",icon:"🔬",color:"var(--sky)",blurb:"Hypotheses, controls and evidence.",questions:[{t:"Logic",q:"To test if a plant needs light, compare it with one that is…",o:["watered more","kept in the dark","given music","painted"],a:1,e:"A control changes only the light to isolate its effect."},{t:"Lateral",q:"One experiment supports your idea. The next step is to…",o:["publish at once","repeat and test more","stop testing","assume proof"],a:1,e:"Single results can be flukes — repetition builds confidence."},{t:"Logic",q:"A result no one else can reproduce is…",o:["definitely true","not yet reliable","a law","magic"],a:1,e:"Reproducibility is what makes a finding trustworthy."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Water boils at 100°C at sea level. High on a mountain it boils at…",o:["a higher temperature","a lower temperature","the same","never"],a:1,e:"Lower air pressure lets water boil cooler."},{t:"Logic",q:"Ice-cream sales and sunburns rise together. This means…",o:["ice cream burns skin","a third cause — the sun","sunburn sells ice cream","nothing"],a:1,e:"Correlation is not cause; sunshine drives both."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Your data has one wildly different point. You should…",o:["delete it quietly","investigate why it differs","ignore all data","round it off"],a:1,e:"Outliers can be errors or discoveries — examine, do not hide."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Which sample gives a more reliable average — 5 people or 5,000?",o:["5","5,000","the same","neither"],a:1,e:"Larger samples smooth out random noise."},{t:"Logic",q:"A good scientific hypothesis must be…",o:["popular","testable","complicated","old"],a:1,e:"If nothing could ever disprove it, it is not science."},{t:"Logic",q:"A drug is tested against a sugar pill so you can…",o:["save money","compare it against no real treatment","skip testing","please patients"],a:1,e:"A placebo control shows whether the drug beats no treatment."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Two test groups differ in many ways at once. It becomes hard to know…",o:["the date","which difference caused the result","their names","the room"],a:1,e:"Many varying factors make cause hard to isolate — control them."},{t:"Logic",q:"The null hypothesis is the starting assumption that…",o:["the treatment works as expected","there is no real effect or no difference between groups","the sample size is adequate","the measurement is valid"],a:1,e:"The null is the default — experiments accumulate evidence that makes it increasingly implausible, until we reject it."},{t:"Logic",q:"Concluding that a drug works when it actually does not — rejecting a true null hypothesis — is called a…",o:["Type II error","Type I error (false positive)","power failure","replication failure"],a:1,e:"Type I error (alpha) produces false alarms. Setting alpha at 0.05 accepts a 5% chance of this mistake by convention."},{t:"Verbal",q:"A p-value of 0.03 means that, IF there were truly no effect, data this extreme would arise by chance about…",o:["3 times out of 10","3 times out of 100","3 times out of 1,000","never"],a:1,e:"p = 0.03 is the probability of the observed result (or more extreme) under the null — not the probability the null is true."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A variable that correlates with both the exposure and the outcome can create an apparent relationship where none exists. This variable is called a…",o:["mediator","confounder","moderator","covariate of interest"],a:1,e:"Confounders distort causal inference — randomisation distributes them evenly; observational studies must measure and adjust for them."},{t:"Logic",q:"In a double-blind trial, neither the participant nor the researcher administering the treatment knows the allocation because…",o:["it saves money","expectation on both sides can measurably influence outcomes and assessments","blinding is always legally required","placebo groups perform worse unblinded"],a:1,e:"Double-blinding eliminates both the placebo response in participants and assessment bias in researchers simultaneously."},{t:"Numbers",q:"You run 20 independent tests each at p < 0.05. By chance alone, the expected number of false positives is about…",o:["0","1","5","10"],a:1,e:"5% × 20 tests = 1 expected false positive even when there are no real effects — the multiple comparisons problem."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Pre-registering a study's hypotheses, methods, and analysis plan before data collection prevents…",o:["large sample sizes","HARKing — Hypothesising After Results are Known — which disguises data mining as planned testing","peer review","replication attempts"],a:1,e:"Pre-registration locks the hypothesis in advance: exploratory findings cannot be presented as confirmatory without disclosure."},{t:"Logic",q:"A large study detects a statistically significant effect with a very small effect size. This result…",o:["is always practically important because it is significant","may be real but practically trivial — large samples detect effects too small to matter clinically or socially","proves causation because of the significance","should be dismissed entirely"],a:1,e:"Statistical significance and practical importance are independent — effect size, not p-value, tells you whether it matters."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Inductive reasoning builds from…",o:["a general rule to a specific conclusion","specific observations upward toward a general pattern or principle","proof to proof in a deductive chain","prediction directly to cause"],a:1,e:"Induction: many observations → tentative general rule. It is the foundation of empirical science — always provisional."},{t:"Lateral",q:"An independent research team attempts to replicate your published finding and fails. The most productive response is to…",o:["dismiss their competence","share raw data and methods openly — discrepancies often reveal hidden methodological assumptions","retract immediately","ignore the failure"],a:1,e:"Failed replications are valuable scientific data — they reveal fragile assumptions, overlooked moderators, or errors on either side."},{t:"Logic",q:"HARKing (Hypothesising After Results are Known) is problematic because it…",o:["requires a large sample","converts exploratory findings into falsely confirmatory ones — inflating the false discovery rate in the literature","is always intentionally fraudulent","reduces statistical power"],a:1,e:"HARKing: a researcher mines data, finds a pattern, then presents it as if it was predicted. The result looks confirmatory but was actually generated by the data."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Cohen's d = 0.8 is conventionally classified as a…",o:["small effect","medium effect","large effect","negligible effect"],a:2,e:"Cohen's benchmarks: d = 0.2 small, 0.5 medium, 0.8 large. These are rough guides — contextual benchmarks in each field matter more."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Bayesian reasoning updates the probability of a hypothesis after seeing new evidence by combining…",o:["the p-value with the sample size","the prior probability with how likely the evidence was under each hypothesis","the null probability with confidence intervals","the mean and the variance"],a:1,e:"Posterior ∝ prior × likelihood. Strong evidence shifts even a stubborn prior; weak evidence barely moves a strong prior."},{t:"Logic",q:"External validity of a study refers to whether…",o:["the measuring instrument is calibrated correctly","the findings generalise beyond the specific sample, setting, and time of the study","the statistical analysis was conducted correctly","the sample size was adequate"],a:1,e:"Internal validity: did we measure what we claim? External validity: does it generalise? Both are required for useful science."},{t:"Pattern",q:"In a forest plot from a meta-analysis, the central diamond at the bottom represents…",o:["the single most important study","the pooled overall effect estimate across all included studies","the study with the lowest p-value","the most recent publication in the set"],a:1,e:"The diamond's centre is the weighted-average pooled effect; its width is the confidence interval for that estimate."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Asymmetry in a funnel plot — where small studies are missing on one side — suggests…",o:["no bias in the literature","publication bias: small negative or null studies are unpublished, inflating the pooled estimate","large studies are biased","the meta-analysis included too few studies"],a:1,e:"Funnel plot asymmetry is a visual test for publication bias — symmetric funnels suggest unbiased publication."},{t:"Logic",q:"Structural equation modelling (SEM) allows researchers to test…",o:["only simple two-variable correlations","complex causal models that include latent variables and multiple simultaneous pathways","group mean differences only","descriptive statistics visually"],a:1,e:"SEM tests entire theoretical frameworks — unmeasured constructs, mediating pathways, and direct effects simultaneously."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A study is designed with 80% statistical power to detect a given effect. This means an 80% chance of detecting the effect IF it is real. Increasing sample size…",o:["reduces power because there is more noise","increases power — larger samples reduce sampling error, making real effects easier to detect","has no effect on power","removes the need for a null hypothesis"],a:1,e:"Power = 1 − β. More participants shrink sampling variability, making the signal clearer relative to the noise."},{t:"Lateral",q:"The Open Science movement promotes pre-registration, open data sharing, and independent replication primarily to…",o:["make research longer and more expensive","make science more transparent and self-correcting — reducing the chance that unreproducible findings persist","eliminate peer review","guarantee that all published findings are true"],a:1,e:"Transparency and independent verification are the infrastructure of trustworthy science — not administrative overhead."},{t:"Logic",q:"Karl Popper's criterion of falsifiability requires that a scientific claim must be…",o:["proven beyond reasonable doubt","testable in a way that could in principle show it to be wrong","accepted by the majority of scientists","published in a peer-reviewed journal"],a:1,e:"A claim that cannot be falsified — no possible observation could count against it — falls outside the domain of science."}]},{id:"pilot",name:"Pilot",icon:"✈️",color:"var(--lantern)",blurb:"Procedures, spatial sense and decisions.",questions:[{t:"Lateral",q:"A warning light comes on mid-flight. First you should…",o:["guess","follow the checklist","switch it off","land anywhere"],a:1,e:"Checklists turn panic into proven, ordered steps."},{t:"Spatial",q:"Heading due North, you turn right 90°. You now head…",o:["South","East","West","North"],a:1,e:"A right turn from North faces East."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Cruising at 600 km/h, how far do you travel in 30 minutes?",o:["150 km","300 km","600 km","1,200 km"],a:1,e:"Half an hour at 600 km/h is 300 km."},{t:"Logic",q:"Two instruments disagree. The safer assumption is…",o:["both are right","one may be faulty","ignore both","trust the prettier one"],a:1,e:"Cross-check; never assume a disagreeing instrument is correct."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Descending 3,000 ft at 1,000 ft per minute takes…",o:["1 minute","3 minutes","30 minutes","300 minutes"],a:1,e:"3,000 ÷ 1,000 = 3 minutes."},{t:"Spatial",q:'A runway marked "09" points roughly toward…',o:["North","East","South","West"],a:1,e:"Runway numbers are the heading ÷ 10 — 09 means about 090°, East."},{t:"Logic",q:"Pre-flight checklists exist mainly to…",o:["look official","stop steps being missed under stress","waste time","slow you down"],a:1,e:"Under pressure, memory fails — the list does not."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Fuel is lower than planned because of headwind. You should…",o:["speed up blindly","reassess and divert if needed","ignore it","climb forever"],a:1,e:"Re-plan with the real numbers rather than hoping."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Climbing 9,000 ft at 1,500 ft per minute takes…",o:["3 min","6 min","9 min","15 min"],a:1,e:"9,000 ÷ 1,500 = 6 minutes."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Weather at the destination turns dangerous. A wise flight plan always includes…",o:["no plan","an alternate airport","flying faster","ignoring it"],a:1,e:"Always carry a diversion option."},{t:"Logic",q:"Class A airspace requires all aircraft to fly under Instrument Flight Rules because…",o:["it is located near mountains","at high altitude and high speed, visual separation between aircraft becomes impractical","it is restricted to military operations","it is always over water"],a:1,e:"Above the transition level, all traffic is IFR — ATC provides separation using radar and position reports."},{t:"Logic",q:"A wing stalls when the critical angle of attack is exceeded. This means a stall can occur…",o:["only at low airspeed","at any airspeed — including cruise — if the angle of attack is too high","only during take-off or landing","only in turbulent conditions"],a:1,e:"Stall is purely about angle of attack, not airspeed. High-g turns can stall a wing at cruise speed."},{t:"Numbers",q:"IFR regulations typically require fuel to reach the destination, then the alternate airport, plus a minimum reserve of…",o:["10 minutes","45 minutes at normal cruise","2 hours","3 hours"],a:1,e:"FAA IFR: destination + alternate + 45-minute reserve. Reserve exists because actual conditions rarely match the plan."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Hypoxia at altitude is particularly insidious because the pilot…",o:["becomes immediately cold and confused","often feels fine or even euphoric while cognitive function is already critically impaired","always notices their vision blurring","can always recover by breathing faster"],a:1,e:"Hypoxia impairs judgement before self-awareness — the pilot cannot reliably detect their own impairment. Supplemental oxygen is required."},{t:"Logic",q:"Spatial disorientation occurs when the vestibular system contradicts the flight instruments because…",o:["the GPS signal is lost","without outside visual references, the inner ear creates false sensations of attitude and motion","turbulence confuses the altimeter","clouds affect the compass"],a:1,e:"The inner ear is unreliable without a visual horizon — in IMC, trust instruments absolutely, not body sensations."},{t:"Verbal",q:"The sterile cockpit rule prohibits non-essential conversation and activity during critical flight phases (below 10,000 ft) because…",o:["passengers prefer silence","distraction during approach and departure is a proven accident cause — attention must be on the aircraft","regulations require it only for training flights","automation handles those phases anyway"],a:1,e:"Most approach and landing accidents involve distraction — the sterile cockpit rule enforces task focus at the highest-risk moments."},{t:"Logic",q:"Wake turbulence from a heavy aircraft is greatest for a following aircraft that is…",o:["heavy and fast","lighter and slower — at low altitude just inside the wake vortex path","at the same weight and speed","flying at high altitude"],a:1,e:"Vortices sink, drift, and persist longest in calm air. A light, slow aircraft following a heavy jet close in is most at risk."},{t:"Numbers",q:"All aircraft above the transition altitude set altimeters to the standard pressure datum of…",o:["local QNH","1013.25 hPa (29.92 inHg)","0 hPa","the airfield elevation datum"],a:1,e:"Standard pressure ensures all aircraft above the transition altitude read altitude consistently relative to each other — critical for separation."},{t:"Spatial",q:"A VASI showing two red lights on final approach means the aircraft is…",o:["on the correct glidepath","below the glidepath and must climb","above the glidepath and must descend","correctly aligned laterally but off glidepath"],a:1,e:"Red over red — you're dead (too low). White over red is right on the path. Two whites means too high."},{t:"Logic",q:"Decision height on a precision instrument approach is the altitude at which the pilot must either…",o:["begin the approach descent","have the runway environment in sight and continue, or execute a missed approach immediately","contact approach control","increase the approach speed"],a:1,e:"Below decision height without visual reference, the aircraft cannot safely continue — delay costs the safety margin the procedure provides."},{t:"Logic",q:"Crew Resource Management (CRM) training primarily targets accidents caused by…",o:["mechanical failure and engine problems","human factors: poor communication, authority gradients, complacency, and failure to use all available information","bad weather conditions","fuel exhaustion"],a:1,e:"Most accidents are human-factors events. CRM trains crews to speak up, cross-check, and use all resources — including each other."},{t:"Numbers",q:"On a 3° glideslope at a groundspeed of 150 knots, the required rate of descent is approximately…",o:["300 ft/min","750 ft/min","1,500 ft/min","200 ft/min"],a:1,e:"Rule of thumb: groundspeed (knots) × 5 = ft/min on a 3° slope. 150 × 5 = 750 ft/min."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Automation bias in glass-cockpit aircraft occurs when flight crew…",o:["hand-fly too frequently during cruise","over-trust the automation and fail to detect errors it is generating — reducing active monitoring","use more checklists than required","improve their manual flying skills"],a:1,e:"Automation bias is a confirmed human-factors hazard — crews must actively monitor, not passively observe."},{t:"Logic",q:"ETOPS (Extended-range Twin-engine Operations) rules govern how far a twin-engine airliner may fly from a diversion airport because…",o:["twin engines use more fuel","if one engine fails, the aircraft must reach an airport within the approved maximum single-engine flying time","twin-engine aircraft are lighter","regulations require more maintenance on twins"],a:1,e:"ETOPS rules exist to limit exposure after a single engine failure — the approved time determines the route."},{t:"Spatial",q:"A microburst on final approach is dangerous because it first produces a headwind that increases lift, then a sudden tailwind that…",o:["corrects the aircraft back to the glidepath","collapses lift and causes rapid airspeed and altitude loss at the most critical moment","has no net effect on airspeed","increases thrust automatically"],a:1,e:"The tailwind phase is the killer — it strips lift when the aircraft is low, slow, and close to the ground."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Density altitude is higher than pressure altitude whenever the temperature is…",o:["below the International Standard Atmosphere (ISA) value","above the ISA standard — hot air is less dense, raising density altitude","exactly at standard conditions","unknown"],a:1,e:"High density altitude means lower air density — longer take-off run, reduced climb rate, and degraded engine performance."},{t:"Logic",q:"An engine failure after take-off (EFATO) demands an immediate decision because…",o:["the aircraft is too fast to steer","there is a minimum safe altitude for any return-to-runway manoeuvre — attempting to turn back below it is usually fatal","ATC must be called first","the autopilot disconnects automatically"],a:1,e:'The "impossible turn" kills pilots who attempt it below roughly 500–1000 ft — land ahead is almost always the correct decision.'},{t:"Lateral",q:"The black-hole illusion on night approaches over dark, featureless terrain causes pilots to believe they are higher than they are, leading to…",o:["flying too high and overshooting","flying too low — undershooting the runway threshold without recognising it","a steeper than normal approach","an unstabilised approach at too high a speed"],a:1,e:"Without terrain cues, the visual system misjudges the approach angle — radar altimeters and PAPI lights provide objective reference."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Threat and Error Management (TEM) models aviation safety by tracking external threats, the errors they generate, and…",o:["weather patterns only","the undesired aircraft states that result from errors — and how well crews recover from them","passenger load factors","fuel cost per route"],a:1,e:"TEM: threats → errors → undesired states → outcomes. Catching and recovering at each stage prevents the final accident."},{t:"Logic",q:"During a declared emergency, the pilot in command has authority to…",o:["deviate from regulations only with prior ATC permission","deviate from any regulation to the minimum extent necessary for the safety of the flight","land without cost at any airport","bypass pre-flight checks only"],a:1,e:"Emergency authority is broad — the PIC may deviate from any FAR or CAR if it is necessary to save life or the aircraft."}]},{id:"chef",name:"Chef",icon:"🍳",color:"var(--berry)",blurb:"Sequencing, ratios and timing.",questions:[{t:"Numbers",q:"A recipe for 2 needs 200g of flour. For 6 people you need…",o:["200g","400g","600g","1,200g"],a:2,e:"Three times the people means three times the flour: 600g."},{t:"Pattern",q:"You boil pasta before adding sauce. This is mostly about…",o:["the colour","the right order of steps","the plate","the price"],a:1,e:"Sequence matters — sauce cannot cook the pasta."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A dish tastes flat. The quickest thing to try first is…",o:["more heat","a pinch of salt","a bigger plate","more oil"],a:1,e:"Salt lifts flavour faster than almost anything else."},{t:"Numbers",q:"One cake bakes in 40 minutes. Two cakes side by side take about…",o:["20 minutes","40 minutes","80 minutes","120 minutes"],a:1,e:"They bake in parallel in the same oven — still about 40."},{t:"Logic",q:"Raw chicken touched a board. Before cutting salad on it you must…",o:["use it as is","wash and sanitise it","wipe it dry","flip it over"],a:1,e:"Cross-contamination is a real food-safety risk."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A dressing is 3 parts oil to 1 part vinegar. For 6 tbsp oil, use…",o:["1 tbsp vinegar","2 tbsp vinegar","3 tbsp vinegar","6 tbsp vinegar"],a:1,e:"6 ÷ 3 = 2 tbsp vinegar keeps the 3:1 ratio."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Guests arrive in 10 minutes but the roast needs 40. Best move…",o:["serve it raw","adjust the menu","cancel dinner","oven on max"],a:1,e:"Switch to something that fits the time; never serve unsafe food."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Prepping everything before cooking (mise en place) mainly helps…",o:["taste only","timing and flow","the bill","decoration"],a:1,e:"With prep done, the cook keeps pace instead of scrambling."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A custard needs 1 egg per 2 servings. For 8 servings you need…",o:["2 eggs","4 eggs","8 eggs","1 egg"],a:1,e:"8 ÷ 2 = 4 eggs."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A sauce is too salty. The safest fix is to…",o:["add more salt","dilute it or add unsalted volume","serve it as is","add more heat"],a:1,e:"Diluting spreads the salt across more food."},{t:"Logic",q:"The Maillard reaction — which browns meat and creates complex flavour compounds — requires surface temperatures above roughly…",o:["100°C","140°C","200°C","60°C"],a:1,e:"At 100°C water boils from the surface, preventing browning. Maillard reactions need dry heat above ~140°C to proceed."},{t:"Logic",q:"Caramelisation differs from the Maillard reaction because caramelisation involves…",o:["amino acids reacting with reducing sugars","sugar molecules breaking down thermally on their own, without any protein present","fat oxidising at high heat","salt dissolving into liquid"],a:1,e:"Maillard requires amino acids + sugars. Caramelisation is purely sugar pyrolysis — different flavours, different temperatures."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A vinaigrette separates quickly because oil and water do not mix. Adding mustard acts as an…",o:["acid to sharpen flavour","emulsifier — its molecules have water-loving and fat-loving ends that stabilise oil droplets in water","antioxidant to extend shelf life","thickener to increase viscosity"],a:1,e:"Emulsifiers surround oil droplets and prevent them from coalescing — a stable emulsion holds together."},{t:"Logic",q:"FIFO (first in, first out) stock rotation in a professional kitchen means…",o:["the freshest stock goes to the front of the shelf","older deliveries are used before newer ones arrive at the front","all stock is used simultaneously","no labelling of delivery dates is needed"],a:1,e:"FIFO prevents new stock hiding old stock — reducing waste and the risk of expired ingredients reaching the pass."},{t:"Numbers",q:"The minimum safe internal temperature for fully cooked chicken is…",o:["60°C","74°C","50°C","90°C"],a:1,e:"74°C (165°F) destroys Salmonella and Campylobacter throughout the meat — lower temperatures leave pathogen risk."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Over-mixing bread dough after the gluten is fully developed makes the final crumb…",o:["lighter and airier","tough and dense — over-working tears the developed gluten network","rise faster before baking","wetter and stickier"],a:1,e:'Gluten is optimal at the "windowpane" stage — the network stretches without tearing. Over-working breaks it down.'},{t:"Logic",q:"Sous vide cooking seals food in bags and cooks at a precise low water temperature mainly to…",o:["cook faster than conventional methods","achieve exact and consistent doneness throughout the food — without risk of the outside overcooking before the inside is done","save energy versus ovens","preserve green vegetable colour only"],a:1,e:"Constant controlled temperature = uniform doneness edge to edge — impossible with any method using high external heat."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Fermentation of bread dough and beer relies on yeast converting sugars into…",o:["salt and water","carbon dioxide and ethanol — CO₂ causes the rise in bread; ethanol is the target in beer","lactic acid and nothing else","oxygen and flavour compounds"],a:1,e:"Yeast ferments sugars anaerobically: CO₂ leavens the dough; ethanol largely bakes off or contributes to beer's alcohol."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A bread recipe is 75% hydration (baker's percentage). For 800 g of flour, the water needed is…",o:["75 g","600 g","800 g","400 g"],a:1,e:"Baker's percentage: 75% × 800 g flour = 600 g water. All ingredients are percentages relative to flour weight."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Resting a steak for several minutes after cooking before cutting improves it mainly by…",o:["cooling it down for safety","allowing muscle fibres to relax and reabsorb juices — cutting immediately floods the board instead of the plate","increasing internal temperature further","allowing the carryover cooking to continue longer"],a:1,e:"Carryover cooking finishes during rest; the relaxed fibres retain moisture that tense, hot fibres would expel under the knife."},{t:"Logic",q:"A hollandaise sauce breaks when overheated because…",o:["butter turns solid","the egg yolk proteins over-coagulate, causing the fat droplets to coalesce and separate from the water phase","the lemon juice evaporates","salt crystals destroy the emulsion"],a:1,e:"Emulsions break when the emulsifier denatures — keep hollandaise below 70°C and it holds; above that, it scrambles."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A lacto-fermentation brine for vegetables typically uses a salt concentration of…",o:["0.5%","2–3%","10%","20%"],a:1,e:"2–3% salt (20–30 g per litre) creates conditions hospitable to lactobacillus while suppressing harmful bacteria."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Blooming powdered gelatine in cold water before adding it to a hot liquid is necessary because…",o:["it flavours the gelatine more deeply","dry granules must absorb water first — adding them directly to hot liquid creates rubbery lumps","cold water increases setting strength","heating gelatine before blooming destroys it"],a:1,e:"Pre-hydration swells the gelatine granules evenly — they then dissolve smoothly into a warm (not boiling) liquid."},{t:"Logic",q:"A reduction sauce concentrates and intensifies flavour because…",o:["adding stock increases flavour compounds","evaporation removes water volume, leaving dissolved flavour compounds at increasing concentration","adding salt during reduction draws out moisture","reducing always adds acidity"],a:1,e:"Evaporation removes water — the dissolved sugars, amino acids, and aromatic compounds remain, concentrating intensely."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Classic béchamel uses equal parts butter and flour by weight for the roux, with milk at roughly…",o:["the same weight as the butter","ten times the weight of the butter","twice the weight of the flour","half the weight of the butter"],a:1,e:"50 g butter, 50 g flour, 500 ml milk — the milk is roughly 10× the fat weight. The roux absorbs it gradually over heat."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Basic spherification (a modernist technique) creates a liquid-centred sphere by reacting sodium alginate in the flavoured liquid with…",o:["hot water only","a calcium chloride setting bath that forms a thin gel membrane around each droplet","gelatine and agar mixed together","liquid nitrogen at −196°C"],a:1,e:"Alginate in the liquid reacts with calcium ions at the bath surface — gel forms instantly at the boundary, leaving the inside liquid."},{t:"Logic",q:"Tempered chocolate — which snaps cleanly and has a glossy finish — is achieved by controlling crystallisation of cocoa butter into stable…",o:["Form I crystals via rapid cooling","Form V crystals via a controlled melt-seed-warm sequence","Form III crystals via freezing","any crystal form via high heat"],a:1,e:"Form V (beta prime) is the stable polymorph — tempering creates it by melting fully, cooling to seed the right crystals, then warming slightly."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Cold-smoking fish is typically carried out at temperatures…",o:["above 100°C","above 75°C","at or below 30°C","below 0°C"],a:2,e:"Cold-smoking at ≤30°C imparts flavour and preservation through smoke compounds without cooking the protein — hot-smoking cooks it."},{t:"Lateral",q:'Transglutaminase ("meat glue") is used in professional kitchens to…',o:["season meat with glutamate","bond protein surfaces of separate pieces together — creating seamless constructed portions without heat or glue","tenderise cheap cuts by breaking down collagen","add umami flavour to broths"],a:1,e:"Transglutaminase cross-links myosin proteins at adjacent surfaces — the pieces bond as strongly as if naturally joined."},{t:"Logic",q:"Fermenting vegetables in a vacuum-sealed anaerobic environment is safer than an open crock because…",o:["the vacuum raises the temperature","excluding oxygen suppresses aerobic mould and harmful bacteria while allowing lactobacillus to thrive","the pressure forces brine into the vegetables faster","light is blocked preventing nutrient loss"],a:1,e:"Lactobacillus is anaerobic — it thrives without oxygen. Aerobic spoilage organisms need air. Remove air, and the right microbes win."}]},{id:"journalist",name:"Journalist",icon:"📰",color:"var(--grape)",blurb:"Verification, sourcing and bias.",questions:[{t:"Lateral",q:"One anonymous source makes a big claim. Before publishing you should…",o:["print it at once","verify with more sources","ignore it","just guess"],a:1,e:"Single unverified claims get confirmed before they run."},{t:"Verbal",q:"Which headline is the most neutral?",o:['"Greedy council forces road"','"Council approves road plan"','"Disaster road approved"','"Heroes save the road"'],a:1,e:"It states what happened without loaded words."},{t:"Logic",q:"A striking photo could be old or edited. First you should…",o:["use it anyway","check its origin and date","just crop it","ignore it"],a:1,e:"Provenance matters — verify before you publish."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A study praising a product was funded by that company. You should…",o:["trust it fully","note the conflict of interest","hide the funding","reject all studies"],a:1,e:"Disclose the conflict so readers can judge."},{t:"Verbal",q:'"Some people say…" with no name attached is…',o:["strong proof","weak and unsourced","a hard fact","a real quote"],a:1,e:'Unnamed "some say" carries almost no weight.'},{t:"Logic",q:"Two eyewitnesses flatly contradict each other. At least one must be…",o:["lying for sure","mistaken or wrong","correct","irrelevant"],a:1,e:"Both cannot be right, but it need not be deliberate."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A story is exciting but you cannot confirm it. The right call is…",o:["publish for clicks","hold it until confirmed","exaggerate it","give up reporting"],a:1,e:"Accuracy beats being first."},{t:"Verbal",q:'"The bridge is 2 km long" is an example of a…',o:["opinion","fact","rumour","prediction"],a:1,e:"It is measurable and verifiable — a fact."},{t:"Logic",q:"A quote is repeated by many outlets, all citing one source. It is really…",o:["many sources","one source repeated","independently confirmed","irrelevant"],a:1,e:"Echoing a single origin is still one source."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A leaked document looks real. Before reporting it you must…",o:["publish at once","verify it is authentic","trust the leaker","ignore it"],a:1,e:"Authenticity must be checked before publishing."},{t:"Verbal",q:'Information shared "on the record" means the journalist may…',o:["never quote it directly","attribute it and quote it with the source's full name","use it only as background without attribution","share it only with an editor"],a:1,e:"On the record: everything said can be quoted and attributed — the most transparent and legally robust form of sourcing."},{t:"Logic",q:"Truth is a complete defence against a defamation claim because…",o:["journalists can publish anything if they believe it","you cannot legally defame someone by publishing a statement that is accurate","editors decide what is defamatory","courts ignore truth in media cases"],a:1,e:"Defamation protects reputation against false statements of fact. Prove the statement is true and the claim falls."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A Freedom of Information request is a legal mechanism allowing the public to obtain…",o:["private company financial accounts","documents and data held by public authorities that would not otherwise be made available","personal correspondence between private citizens","social media posts from public figures"],a:1,e:"FOI is an investigative cornerstone — government decisions, spending, and communications can be obtained by law."},{t:"Logic",q:"False equivalence in coverage occurs when…",o:["both sides of a debate are researched equally thoroughly","a fringe minority view is given equal platform to a strong evidential consensus — implying they are equivalent","only one side is presented","statistics are used without context"],a:1,e:"False balance is not journalistic fairness — presenting 97 scientists and 3 dissenters as equally credible actively misleads."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A headline claims a disease rate doubled. The original rate was 1 in 500,000. The new rate is…",o:["enormous — 50% of the population","2 in 500,000 — still extremely rare despite the alarming-sounding percentage rise","100 in 500,000","the headline is misleading"],a:1,e:"Percentage changes on tiny baselines sound dramatic while the absolute numbers remain negligible — always report both."},{t:"Lateral",q:"The hostile media effect describes the tendency for people with strong prior views to perceive balanced coverage as…",o:["fair and well-researched","biased against their own side — regardless of the actual balance of the reporting","too neutral to be useful","supporting the other side intentionally"],a:1,e:"Partisans on both sides consistently perceive neutral reporting as hostile to them — making balance complaints inherently unreliable as feedback."},{t:"Logic",q:"Information given off the record may be used by the journalist to…",o:["quote directly, attributing it to the source","guide investigation and find confirmable on-the-record sources for the same information","publish with a pseudonym instead","never — it is completely off limits"],a:1,e:"Off the record does not mean unusable — it informs the journalist's pursuit of provable, attributable evidence."},{t:"Verbal",q:"Plagiarism in journalism means…",o:["quoting a source with clear attribution","reproducing another person's words, ideas, or work and presenting them as your own without credit","summarising a public speech","interviewing the same source a competitor used"],a:1,e:"Plagiarism is a cardinal professional offence — it deceives readers and editors while stealing the original creator's labour."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A chart with a Y-axis that starts at 90 instead of 0 when comparing values of 91% and 95% is misleading because it makes a 4-point difference appear…",o:["smaller than it is","proportionally enormous — visually amplifying the gap far beyond its true magnitude","accurate — the zoom is appropriate","irrelevant to readers"],a:1,e:"Truncated axes exploit visual perception: a 4% gap can visually look like a 400% difference when the baseline is hidden."},{t:"Logic",q:"Confirmation bias in journalism leads reporters to…",o:["verify all claims rigorously before publishing","seek out sources and evidence that align with a pre-existing narrative angle, unconsciously discounting what contradicts it","ignore tips that come in late","publish more slowly to ensure accuracy"],a:1,e:"Confirmation bias is invisible from the inside — the defence is actively commissioning disconfirming evidence, not relying on feeling balanced."},{t:"Lateral",q:"The deepfake threat to journalism primarily concerns the…",o:["cost of video production equipment","ability to synthesise convincing video and audio of real people saying things they never said","speed of news distribution","monetisation of video content"],a:1,e:"Synthetic media breaks the instinct to trust video evidence — verification methods must catch up with generation methods."},{t:"Logic",q:"Structural bias in news coverage refers to…",o:["individual reporter prejudice against specific politicians","systemic pressures — commercial, access-driven, deadline-driven — that shape what gets covered regardless of any individual's intent","ownership interference in specific stories","geographic proximity to events"],a:1,e:"Structural forces produce patterned blind spots more reliably than individual malice — understanding them requires systemic analysis, not just blaming reporters."},{t:"Verbal",q:"Shield laws protect journalists specifically from…",o:["defamation claims by sources","being compelled by courts to reveal the identity of confidential sources","copyright infringement suits","libel actions from public figures"],a:1,e:"Shield protection is critical to public-interest journalism — without it, sources dry up and investigative reporting becomes impossible."},{t:"Logic",q:"An embargo on a story means it may be published…",o:["immediately after receiving it","only from the specific date and time agreed with the source or institution","at the journalist's discretion","only after a second source confirms it"],a:1,e:"Breaking an embargo damages trust and future access — it is a professional norm with real consequences, not just a courtesy."},{t:"Lateral",q:"The availability heuristic distorts public perception of risk because vivid and memorable events…",o:["are always statistically more common","feel more likely than they statistically are — air crashes feel more dangerous than car crashes despite the inverse being true","are always reported accurately","reduce fear through familiarity"],a:1,e:"Memorable events are cognitively available — journalism that disproportionately covers dramatic events inflates perceived risk."},{t:"Logic",q:"Proportionality in crime reporting means the volume of coverage should roughly reflect…",o:["how dramatic and visually compelling the story is","the actual prevalence and social impact of the crime — not just its newsworthiness or shock value","the reporter's personal interest in the case","the number of social media clicks the story generates"],a:1,e:"Disproportionate coverage of rare violent crime consistently distorts the public's perception of personal safety."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Investigative journalism differs from daily news primarily in its emphasis on…",o:["publishing speed and volume","depth, original document analysis, and independently establishing facts rather than reporting statements","broadcast reach and social sharing","interview-based celebrity access"],a:1,e:"Investigations are deliberately slow — documents, data, source triangulation and legal review take weeks or months."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A quote from a politician goes viral. Before reporting it, the journalist must verify…",o:["that it has a high number of shares and reactions","the original source, full context, whether the quote is accurately transcribed, and that it is not from a parody account","that it is trending internationally","that other outlets have already reported it"],a:1,e:"Virality is not verification — decontextualised, fabricated, and satirical content spreads fastest precisely because it is surprising."},{t:"Logic",q:"The Chatham House Rule allows attendees of a meeting to freely use information from the discussion, but prohibits…",o:["taking notes during the session","identifying the speaker or their organisation in any way","attending future meetings at the institution","sharing the content with colleagues"],a:1,e:"Chatham House: the content is free; the attribution is protected — enabling candour from speakers who could not otherwise speak openly."},{t:"Verbal",q:"A clear and credible journalistic correction policy requires that errors are…",o:["quietly deleted from the original article","acknowledged promptly, corrected visibly, and if significant, explained in a dedicated correction notice","blamed on the original source where possible","corrected only if the subject of the story complains"],a:1,e:"Transparent corrections build long-term credibility — concealing errors destroys it faster than the original mistake."}]},{id:"architect",name:"Architect",icon:"📐",color:"var(--clay)",blurb:"Space, constraints and structure.",questions:[{t:"Spatial",q:"A room 4 m by 5 m has a floor area of…",o:["9 m²","20 m²","40 m²","45 m²"],a:1,e:"Area = length × width = 4 × 5 = 20 m²."},{t:"Logic",q:"A design must fit both the budget and the site. If it busts the budget it is…",o:["perfect","not yet viable","already built","automatically cheap"],a:1,e:"A constraint that fails means back to the drawing board."},{t:"Spatial",q:"To catch morning light, big windows are best facing…",o:["North","East","West","underground"],a:1,e:"The sun rises in the East, so east-facing windows catch the morning."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Clients want more rooms on the same footprint. One real option is to…",o:["ignore them","build upward, add a floor","only remove walls","shrink the land"],a:1,e:"When you cannot spread out, you go up."},{t:"Logic",q:"Load-bearing walls mainly exist to…",o:["decorate","hold the structure up","save paint","block sound only"],a:1,e:"Remove one carelessly and the building can fail."},{t:"Spatial",q:"Doubling the side length of a square room multiplies its floor area by…",o:["2","3","4","8"],a:2,e:"Area scales with the side squared — double the side, four times the area."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A beautiful building ignores how people move through it. The flaw is…",o:["the colour","poor flow and usability","it is too cheap","small windows"],a:1,e:"Good architecture serves how people actually use the space."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A staircase must rise 3 m using steps 0.15 m tall. That needs…",o:["10 steps","15 steps","20 steps","30 steps"],a:2,e:"3 ÷ 0.15 = 20 steps."},{t:"Spatial",q:"A corridor is 2 m wide and 10 m long. Its floor area is…",o:["12 m²","20 m²","5 m²","100 m²"],a:1,e:"2 × 10 = 20 m²."},{t:"Logic",q:"A fire exit would be blocked by a planned wall. The design must…",o:["keep the wall","keep a clear exit","remove the exit","ignore safety"],a:1,e:"Safe escape is a hard requirement — the exit wins."},{t:"Logic",q:"Net floor area differs from gross floor area because net area excludes…",o:["the main rooms tenants occupy","walls, lift shafts, plant rooms, and circulation space — only the usable area counts","all glazed surfaces","the foundation slab"],a:1,e:"Gross area includes structure and shared spaces; net area is what tenants can actually occupy and rent."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A wall with a U-value of 0.15 W/m²K compared with one at 3.0 W/m²K…",o:["performs the same thermally","loses twenty times less heat per square metre per degree of temperature difference","performs worse","only differs in cost"],a:1,e:"Lower U-value = better insulation. 3.0 is single-glazing territory; 0.15 approaches Passivhaus wall performance."},{t:"Logic",q:"Fire egress regulations specify maximum travel distances to exits primarily to ensure…",o:["aesthetic uniformity in corridor lengths","occupants can reach safety before conditions in the escape route become untenable","structural loads are evenly distributed","sprinkler systems have adequate coverage"],a:1,e:"Travel distance limits are hard life-safety law — exceed them and the design cannot obtain Building Regulations approval."},{t:"Lateral",q:"BIM (Building Information Modelling) goes beyond 3D drawing by embedding…",o:["only visual geometry and rendering quality","data about materials, cost, programme, energy performance, and maintenance into a shared, coordinated model","structural calculations only","planning drawings in digital format"],a:1,e:"BIM is a living data platform — the model is a shared source of truth for the entire project lifecycle, not just geometry."},{t:"Logic",q:"Embodied carbon in a building refers to emissions from…",o:["heating, cooling, and lighting during building operation","material extraction, manufacture, transport, and construction — locked in before the building first opens","occupant commuting","site landscaping and planting"],a:1,e:"As operational carbon falls through better energy standards, embodied carbon is becoming the dominant share of lifetime impact."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A Passivhaus (Passive House) building achieves very low heating demand mainly through…",o:["ground-source heat pumps as the primary system","a super-insulated, airtight envelope with controlled mechanical ventilation and heat recovery","solar panels providing all energy needs","south-facing glass alone"],a:1,e:"Passivhaus heating demand is ≤15 kWh/m²/yr — achieved by eliminating heat loss through fabric, not just adding renewables."},{t:"Logic",q:"Post-occupancy evaluation (POE) examines whether a completed building…",o:["received its planning permission on schedule","performs as designed and genuinely meets user needs in practice — closing the feedback loop","looks as intended in photographs","cost less than the original budget estimate"],a:1,e:"Most buildings are never evaluated against their design intent. POE is how the profession learns from what it actually builds."},{t:"Spatial",q:"A correctly sized horizontal overhang on a south-facing window blocks high summer sun but admits low winter sun because…",o:["winter sun does not reach south-facing facades","the sun's arc is higher in summer and much lower in winter — the overhang depth exploits this geometry","overhangs redirect light optically","glass transmits winter sun differently"],a:1,e:"Sun angle varies by season — a fixed overhang can be designed to shade the summer sun exactly while missing the winter sun."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A room 8 m × 10 m has a window 2.5 m wide and 1.4 m tall. The window-to-floor area ratio is…",o:["4.4%","30%","15%","8%"],a:0,e:"Window area = 2.5 × 1.4 = 3.5 m²; floor area = 80 m²; 3.5 ÷ 80 ≈ 4.4%. Good daylighting targets 10–20%."},{t:"Lateral",q:"High thermal mass — exposed concrete slab or dense masonry — improves occupant comfort by…",o:["reducing the structural frame size","absorbing heat during the day and releasing it slowly at night, smoothing internal temperature swings","adding acoustic dampening to ceiling surfaces","reducing window sizes required for thermal performance"],a:1,e:"Thermal mass is a flywheel — it shifts peak temperature by hours and reduces the swings that mechanical systems otherwise must chase."},{t:"Logic",q:"The critical path in a construction programme is the sequence of activities where any delay…",o:["can be absorbed within existing float","directly delays the project completion date — there is zero float on these activities","affects only the final fit-out phase","triggers a contractual penalty automatically"],a:1,e:"Critical path = zero float. Every day's slip on a critical-path activity is a day lost on completion unless acceleration is applied."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A steel beam with second moment of area (I) nine times greater than a reference beam deflects under the same load…",o:["nine times more","nine times less","three times less","the same amount"],a:1,e:"Deflection is inversely proportional to I — nine times the stiffness means one-ninth the deflection."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Biophilic design — incorporating natural light, planting, views of nature, and natural materials — is valued in buildings because research shows it…",o:["reduces construction cost","measurably improves occupant wellbeing, cognitive performance, and stress recovery compared with inert artificial environments","simplifies structural engineering","makes planning approval faster"],a:1,e:"Evidence links biophilic environments to lower cortisol, faster healing in hospitals, and higher productivity in workplaces."},{t:"Logic",q:"Party wall agreements are legally required before building work that…",o:["changes the interior layout without touching external walls","affects or is structurally close to a shared boundary wall with an adjoining owner's property","involves repainting the exterior facade","replaces windows on a non-party elevation"],a:1,e:"The Party Wall etc. Act 1996 protects adjoining owners — notifiable works require a formal agreement or award before starting."},{t:"Pattern",q:"A Section 106 planning obligation requires a developer to…",o:["submit structural calculations in the agreed format","contribute financially or in kind to local infrastructure or affordable housing as a condition of planning consent","insure the building against subsidence for 10 years","provide a BIM model to the planning authority"],a:1,e:"S106 obligations offset the impact of development on surrounding public services and community needs — negotiated with the LPA."},{t:"Spatial",q:"A drawing that cuts through a building on a vertical plane to reveal floor-to-floor heights, structural depth, and internal relationships is a…",o:["site plan","reflected ceiling plan","section drawing","perspective view"],a:2,e:"Sections cut the building open vertically — the most informative drawing type for understanding spatial proportions and structure."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Adaptive reuse of an existing building structure often has lower lifecycle carbon than demolishing and building new because…",o:["planning permission is always faster","the existing structure and envelope already embody decades of energy — preserving them avoids the carbon cost of new material production","construction costs are always lower","new buildings cannot match old craftsmanship"],a:1,e:"The embodied carbon in a concrete frame is already spent. Retaining it avoids a new manufacturing cycle — often the most impactful carbon decision on a site."},{t:"Logic",q:"Supplementary Planning Documents (SPDs) differ from the Local Plan policies they supplement because SPDs…",o:["override national planning policy","provide detailed guidance on applying adopted Local Plan policies — they are material considerations, not policy themselves","are written by developers, not the planning authority","can be used to refuse planning applications independently"],a:1,e:"SPDs guide interpretation of policies but are subordinate to the Local Plan and National Planning Policy Framework."},{t:"Numbers",q:"A corridor needs 800 lux but currently measures 200 lux. The percentage increase in light output required is…",o:["60%","300%","400%","200%"],a:1,e:"(800 − 200) ÷ 200 × 100 = 300%. The increase is calculated relative to the starting level, not the target."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Value engineering applied to a design aims to…",o:["increase specification to improve quality at any cost","achieve equivalent or better function at reduced cost by systematically questioning whether every element earns its place","reduce quality across the board to meet budget","extend the construction programme to reduce risk"],a:1,e:"True value engineering is analytical, not just cost-cutting — it targets unnecessary complexity without sacrificing performance."}]},{id:"detective",name:"Detective",icon:"🕵️",color:"var(--sky)",blurb:"Deduction, evidence and inference.",questions:[{t:"Logic",q:"A room was locked from inside, but a window stood open. The likely exit is…",o:["the door","the window","the chimney","no exit at all"],a:1,e:"The only unsecured opening is the most likely route."},{t:"Logic",q:"A suspect was filmed across town when the crime happened. They are…",o:["guilty","likely cleared","definitely lying","still the main suspect"],a:1,e:"A solid alibi removes them from the scene."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Footprints stop suddenly in soft mud. A reasonable inference is…",o:["the person vanished","they left another way, perhaps a vehicle","it was magic","ignore it"],a:1,e:"People do not vanish — look for how the trail changed."},{t:"Logic",q:"Only the gardener had a key and the room was locked. That makes the gardener…",o:["guilty for certain","a strong lead, not yet proof","clearly innocent","just a witness"],a:1,e:"Opportunity points at them, but you still need proof."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Two clues point one way and one points the other. You should…",o:["ignore the odd clue","re-examine the odd clue","flip a coin","close the case"],a:1,e:"The clue that does not fit often hides the real story."},{t:"Logic",q:"After a thorough search, finding no evidence is…",o:["proof of innocence","suggestive but not proof","proof of guilt","irrelevant"],a:1,e:"Absence of evidence is weak evidence, not certainty."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A confession contradicts the physical evidence. It should be…",o:["trusted completely","checked against the evidence","ignored","celebrated"],a:1,e:"Facts outrank words — verify before believing."},{t:"Logic",q:"A suspect with motive, means and opportunity is…",o:["guilty for sure","a prime suspect who still needs proof","automatically cleared","only a witness"],a:1,e:"All three together is strong — but proof still decides."},{t:"Logic",q:"A witness changes their story each time. Their account is…",o:["fully reliable","less reliable","solid proof","irrelevant"],a:1,e:"Inconsistency lowers reliability."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Mud on the suspect's shoes matches the garden, not the street. This is…",o:["meaningless","evidence placing them in the garden","proof of innocence","a pure coincidence"],a:1,e:"Matching trace evidence links them to a specific place."},{t:"Logic",q:"A documented chain of custody for physical evidence exists to prove that the item…",o:["was expensive to collect and store","was not tampered with or substituted between the point of discovery and its presentation in court","was found by a senior officer","matches the crime scene photograph exactly"],a:1,e:"Any gap in the chain gives the defence grounds to challenge whether the exhibit in court is genuine and untainted."},{t:"Logic",q:"Locard's exchange principle states that every contact between a person and a scene…",o:["leaves no trace if the person is careful","transfers trace material both ways — the perpetrator both deposits evidence and carries evidence away","is only useful when the suspect is known","requires technology to detect"],a:1,e:"Locard: contact means exchange. Hair, fibres, soil, pollen — each can link a suspect to a scene or victim bidirectionally."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Circumstantial evidence differs from direct evidence in that it…",o:["is always weaker in court and cannot secure conviction","requires the jury to draw an inference rather than directly witnessing or proving the fact — but can be very strong when multiple strands converge","is never admitted in serious criminal trials","requires corroboration by statute in all jurisdictions"],a:1,e:"Many secure convictions rest entirely on circumstantial evidence — its strength lies in the convergence of independent strands."},{t:"Logic",q:"Confirmation bias during an investigation leads detectives to…",o:["weigh all evidence equally regardless of source","pursue leads that support the current suspect theory while unconsciously discounting contradictory evidence — a documented cause of wrongful conviction","expand the suspect pool early in the investigation","re-examine the scene with fresh eyes routinely"],a:1,e:"Tunnel vision from confirmation bias consistently appears in wrongful conviction case reviews — structural safeguards are required, not just awareness."},{t:"Lateral",q:"False confessions during interrogation occur partly because…",o:["innocent people always behave calmly under questioning","prolonged psychological pressure, sleep deprivation, and highly suggestive questioning can break an innocent person's resistance to false admission","police training prevents coercive conditions","confessions are always cross-checked before charge"],a:1,e:"False confessions are a documented, recurring cause of wrongful conviction — not rare edge cases. Recording and regulation of interrogation are essential."},{t:"Logic",q:"A cognitive interview technique improves witness recall by using…",o:["rapid, repetitive questioning to spot inconsistencies","open-ended prompts, context reinstatement, and mental reinstatement of the event rather than leading questions","mild pressure to trigger memory under stress","multiple interviewers to create urgency"],a:1,e:"Cognitive interviews are evidence-based: free recall, context reinstatement, varied order, and changed perspective each independently boost accuracy."},{t:"Spatial",q:"Geographic profiling uses the spatial pattern of a linked series of crime sites to estimate…",o:["the next crime's precise location","the probable anchor point — home, workplace, or base — of the offender within a prioritised search area","the offender's physical description","when the next offence will occur"],a:1,e:"Offenders typically commit crimes in geographic zones relative to where they live or work. Profiling narrows where to look, not who to look for."},{t:"Pattern",q:"An offender's MO (modus operandi) refers to the…",o:["psychological motive for the offences","consistent method and behaviour pattern used across offences — tools, approach, target type, and sequence","the physical description of the suspect","the category of crime committed"],a:1,e:"MO links offences to a single actor and evolves as the offender learns — changes in MO can reflect experience or circumstance."},{t:"Logic",q:"Physical evidence is generally considered more reliable than eyewitness testimony in serious cases because…",o:["physical evidence is always collected correctly","eyewitness memory is reconstructive, highly susceptible to post-event suggestion, and is the leading contributor to wrongful convictions","juries prefer physical exhibits","eyewitnesses are rarely available in serious crime"],a:1,e:"Eyewitness confidence bears little relationship to accuracy — memory is not a recording, it is reconstructed each time it is retrieved."},{t:"Lateral",q:'The "CSI effect" has reportedly caused juries to…',o:["accept circumstantial evidence more readily","expect forensic evidence in every case and acquit where it is absent — even when other strong evidence exists","trust eyewitnesses more than before","reduce their standard for conviction"],a:1,e:"TV forensic drama has raised jury expectations far beyond what real investigations typically produce — prosecutors must now manage the gap."},{t:"Logic",q:"DNA evidence placing a suspect's material at a crime scene proves…",o:["the suspect committed the crime","that biological contact occurred — but not necessarily when or in what circumstance, requiring additional evidence to interpret","the suspect has no alibi","the suspect was present during the offence"],a:1,e:"DNA proves contact; it does not prove the suspect was present at the time of the offence. Innocent explanations must be excluded."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Victimology — studying the victim's background, routine, and relationships — helps investigators because…",o:["it shifts blame to the victim","understanding why this person was targeted often reveals suspect categories, likely locations, and relationship types to investigate","it satisfies media interest in the victim's story","it reduces the number of suspects to interview"],a:1,e:"The victim's life explains the offender's choice — victimology narrows the suspect field by working backward from why this person, why here."},{t:"Logic",q:"An anonymous tip must be corroborated with independent evidence before it can support a search warrant because…",o:["all tips are assumed false","an uncorroborated anonymous claim lacks sufficient reliability — the court needs a basis to assess the information's credibility","police never act on anonymous tips","warrants are not required for arrests"],a:1,e:"Courts require demonstrated reliability before authorising intrusive state action — corroboration is the constitutional check."},{t:"Pattern",q:"Offender profiling is most accurately described as a tool for…",o:["identifying the specific offender by name and address","narrowing and prioritising the pool of suspects and guiding investigative resource allocation — not as evidence","proving guilt beyond reasonable doubt","replacing forensic evidence in serious cases"],a:1,e:"Profiling is probabilistic — it generates investigative leads, not identifications. It must never substitute for evidence."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Two witnesses who had no contact with each other independently describe the same specific unusual detail. This…",o:["proves the detail was fabricated by coaching","significantly raises the probability the detail is real — independent convergence on specifics is hard to explain by chance or collusion","is a coincidence that should be ignored","proves the detail is in official records somewhere"],a:1,e:"Independent corroboration of specific details is powerful because coordination to achieve it is difficult — each report adds multiplicative weight."},{t:"Logic",q:"The presumption of innocence places the burden of proof on…",o:["the defence to prove innocence","the prosecution to prove guilt beyond reasonable doubt","the judge to assess the most likely account","the jury to investigate independently"],a:1,e:"The state carries the burden entirely — the defendant need prove nothing. This asymmetry is the foundation of a fair criminal justice system."},{t:"Numbers",q:"Of 500 CCTV cameras covering a transport hub, 60% are operational on a given day. The number providing live footage is…",o:["60","200","300","440"],a:2,e:"60% of 500 = 300 working cameras. The other 200 represent a significant coverage gap."},{t:"Lateral",q:"A suspect's mobile phone location data, payment card records, and search history are valuable investigative tools because they…",o:["are always legally admissible without a warrant","provide timestamped, objective records of movement and activity that are difficult to fabricate and can corroborate or contradict alibi claims","replace all other evidence in digital-age investigations","are only useful if the suspect is already known"],a:1,e:"Digital footprints are resistant to the distortions of human memory — a phone's record of where it was is harder to dispute than what a person says they remember."},{t:"Logic",q:"When physical evidence directly contradicts a confession, best practice is to…",o:["accept the confession as the more reliable account","prioritise and re-examine the physical evidence — it is not susceptible to the pressures that produce false confessions","discard the physical evidence","keep both accounts and let the jury decide without guidance"],a:1,e:"Physical evidence is objective; confessions are produced by human beings under interrogation conditions. When they conflict, examine why, and trust the physical."},{t:"Lateral",q:"Research by the Innocence Project into overturned convictions shows that the single most common cause of wrongful conviction is…",o:["poor legal representation at trial","eyewitness misidentification — present in more than half of all documented wrongful conviction cases","prosecutorial misconduct only","fabricated physical evidence"],a:1,e:"Eyewitness error is the leading driver of wrongful convictions worldwide — not rare exceptions, but a systemic failure of how we rely on memory."}]}];export{e as P};
